commit_message:
MAINTAINERS.rst: Add MidoNet section

While the most part of MidoNet code is now externally maintained
using the external plugin mechanism, it can be still useful to
have a contact list.

Change-Id: I3e0a0586c07875ca37ce101dd169eaf78f34f7a5

commit_message:
Fix failed wizard tests

After refactoring angular wizard widget, some API
method defined in scope no longer exist. Removing
those tests against removed the APIs.

Change-Id: I72f64f1a11dad7501c2419f474b21463b90f2149
Closes-Bug: #1462134

Add functional tests from Tempest

- Add separate testenv for functional tests
- Copy Heat templates and tests from tempest
- Add requirements tempest-lib
- Add base class to functional tests

Partial-Bug: #1446442

[{'created': '2015-05-29 15:28:25.000000000', 'message': "Hyper-V: Fixes cold migration / resize issue

Commit 3e42c7ae3f7a9353834c8c9c4dc79ee39dd0783b changed where the Hyper-V
VM configuration files are stored. The files are being stored in the same
folder as the instance. Performing a cold resize / migration will cause a
os.rename call on the instance's folder, which fails as long as there are
configuration files used by Hyper-V in that folder, thus resulting in a
failed migration and the instance ending up in ERROR state.

Hyper-V configuration files are stored in a subfolder of the instance's
folder (e.g.: C:\OpenStack\Instances\instance-000000b6\Virtual Machines).

This commit makes sure that Hyper-V configuration files are not being
moved during migration by skipping subfolders in the instance's folder.

Change-Id: I4874eed7d284fab241e4371e550a88270ca156f1
Closes-Bug: #1453835
(cherry picked from commit acf95831c8550afa3a0e1345d97665063b53acd9)
"}]
commit_message:
Hyper-V: Fixes cold migration / resize issue

Commit 3e42c7ae3f7a9353834c8c9c4dc79ee39dd0783b changed where the Hyper-V
VM configuration files are stored. The files are being stored in the same
folder as the instance. Performing a cold resize / migration will cause a
os.rename call on the instance's folder, which fails as long as there are
configuration files used by Hyper-V in that folder, thus resulting in a
failed migration and the instance ending up in ERROR state.

Hyper-V configuration files are stored in a subfolder of the instance's
folder (e.g.: C:\OpenStack\Instances\instance-000000b6\Virtual Machines).

This commit makes sure that Hyper-V configuration files are not being
moved during migration by skipping subfolders in the instance's folder.

Change-Id: I4874eed7d284fab241e4371e550a88270ca156f1
Closes-Bug: #1453835
(cherry picked from commit acf95831c8550afa3a0e1345d97665063b53acd9)

commit_message:
Change the restart_rpc_backend loop to accomodate async rabbitmq

Some distros have converted to systemd for starting RabbitMQ.  This has
resulted in:
---
[Call Trace]
./stack.sh:904:restart_rpc_backend
/home/stack/projects/openstack/openstack-dev/devstack/lib/rpc_backend:201:die
[ERROR] /home/stack/projects/openstack/openstack-dev/devstack/lib/rpc_backend:201 Failed to set rabbitmq password
Error on exit
World dumping... see /opt/stack/logs/worlddump-2015-05-29-031618.txt for details
---

Because 'restart_service rabbitmq-server' returns before the server is ready to
accept connections.

Alter the retry loop to only restart the rabbitmq-server every second time
through the loop.  Allowing time for the slow rabbit to start.

Closes-Bug: 1449056
Change-Id: Ibb291c1ecfd109f9ed10b5f194933364985cc1ce

I'm in favour in theory, but I think there should be a comment with a reference to the "known NUMA topology issue" rather than just saying "trust me, it's bad".  Maybe even just link to the bug report for #1449028.

Have you tested whether it is fixed there?'}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2015-05-18 10:58:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2015-05-18 11:02:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Done.

> Incidentally, how is it that libvirt broke something in a stable release? Has this issue been reported to the libvirt team?

No, I haven't reported this issue. However, as you say 1.2.9.3 is out now and has resolved this issue. It's not possible to fix 1.2.9.2 in the wild so we'll have to let it go.

> Lastly, I don't see any obvious "fix NUMA topology" item for 1.2.9.3. Have you tested whether it is fixed there?

I missed the 1.2.9.3 release. I've since tested it (it works) and updated the bug report with findings.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-18 11:58:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
libvirt: Disable NUMA for broken libvirt

Ensure versions of libvirt with broken NUMA tuning support are not used
for said feature.

Change-Id: I6de388f1ca98c1ae16f2968f59881e3b0dba5f8d
Closes-Bug: #1449028
Related-Bug: #1438226

commit_message:
cap WSME to <0.7

WSME 0.7 was released fixing a bunch of bugs including one which
changes the validation of input. this causes breaking changes so
let's cap WSME for kilo

Depends-On: I880cffbe003a27e9caba3695e39e39e3bd9b1fcc
Change-Id: Ib8545d44a9faee42bd221c2c9b88123671aa4637
Closes-Bug: #1460869

commit_message:
Deleting VM ports on cluster delete flow

- modified delete port task to take a list of ports and delete all
  specified ports as well as taking a single port
- delete port task also does not throw an exception upon failure to
  delete a port, it instead logs a warning
- modified delete cluster flow to retrieve a list of ports for a VM and
  attempt to delete each port after deleting the VM

Change-Id: Ib311b23fdf3a58bc4b79257ed412e9d53d039013
closes-bug: 1448140

commit_message:
libvirt: introduce method get_guest to Host object

Adds method get_guest to the Host object and updates
the libvirt driver code to use it.

Change-Id: I2923cd939b8dc0dd50799df6d36df31ecc6d8cb1

commit_message:
Follow symlink for elements

This allow custom elements to be added with symlink. Without -follow
a symlinked element is valid but scripts in *.d directory aren't used.

Change-Id: If50b7d9c3b1f6fe278c28488146709efe5cf065f
Closes-Bug: 1461124

commit_message:
Remove instance param from connect/disconnect disk

The disk driver methods connect_disk and disconnect_image_disk were
accepting an 'instance' parameter and an 'lpar_uuid' parameter, but only
using the latter.  In preparation for forthcoming changes whereby disks
can be connected/disconnected to/from something other than an instance
(i.e. the management partition), this change set removes the unused
'instance' parameter from both methods.

Change-Id: Iea6e4647438c1a62b4ed4a9ae3127645253cd543

Change-Id: I1b32f67f78b369f6134a74cdf9a4811b7539d44b
"}, {'created': '2015-05-30 02:54:27.000000000', 'message': "add --domain argument to v3 project set

Currently argument 'domain' is not supported by command 'os project
set', but it is required by keystone v3 update project API to match
the domain id.

Closes-Bug: #1460122
Change-Id: I1b32f67f78b369f6134a74cdf9a4811b7539d44b
"}]
commit_message:
add --domain argument to v3 project set

Currently argument 'domain' is not supported by command 'os project
set', but it is required by keystone v3 update project API to match
the domain id.

Closes-Bug: #1460122
Change-Id: I1b32f67f78b369f6134a74cdf9a4811b7539d44b

commit_message:
Add Ironic API version to passthru URL for deploy-ironic

Add current version of Ironic API for consistensy with IPA and Ironic
API settings, and for compatibility in the future.

Change-Id: I13c7a26b6cfb47a14aa49ee78441a1d97d7b42d0

commit_message:
Enable random hash seeds

neutron-lbaas tests have been updated in order to support random hash
seed. It allows to remove PYTHONHASHSEED=0 in tox.ini and remove
hashtest tox environment.

Closes-Bug: #1348818
Change-Id: I7dce768feeb7c34cdd67bcd54a253d97f4e88f4e

commit_message:
Do not assume jsonutils.dumps ordering

This fixes the unit tests[1] that breaks with a randomized
PYTHONHASHSEED (see the bug report).

The test assumed that the oslo_serializarion.jsonutils.dumps performs
dictionary json dump in particular order. Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=1.

The fix refactors the test case by disabling json dumps and comparing
dictionnaries instead of their json dumps.

[1] neutron_fwaas.tests.unit.services.firewall.drivers.mcafee.\
    test_ngfw_fwaas:
  NGFWFwaasTestCase.test_create_firewall
  NGFWFwaasTestCase.test_update_firewall

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will
be addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: I67fe1ab69bcfd99c2e778963b97c0d6b4b039802

commit_message:
Add unit tests for basic auth methods in token clients

This commit adds the first missing unit tests to the token clients.
Previously there was no coverage at all for these clients so
there was no in-tree method for verifying the functionality of these
classes. The coverage of this commit is limited and only covers 2
basic uses of the auth() method in both the v2 and v3 token clients.
It will be expanded in future patches. As part of enabling this
coverage the fake_http class had to be modified to return a user
provided body and response code.

Change-Id: I1888b31550e5db4343003b05c0f6865444756789

commit_message:
libvirt: introduce a Guest to wrap around virDomain

Introduces object Guest to wrap around virDomain object
and provide a higher level API.
With the introduction of this new class also update _create_domain
logic and update tests.

Next patches will clean code in drivers to use this
new implementation.

Note about Copyrights, they have been copied from
libvirt/driver.py and libvirt/test_driver.py since several
parts of the code from those files will be moved in
guests.py and test_guest.py

Change-Id: I2d193ae44a4ac48ad863d237172cf2c1da05e3e9

[{'created': '2015-06-01 20:41:44.000000000', 'message': 'Use "Rollcall-Vote" for TC and infra-council

Adopt the idea that a review label name should be as
widely-applicable as possible for a given concept so that different
repos with similar needs will end up sharing columns in the user
interface.  Since the TC and infra-specs repos both need "votes from
the people who are members of the committee" as a review label
(while preserving the ability for non-members to leave their feedback
as +/- entries in code-review), have them share the name "Rollcall
Vote".  This will cause them both to appear in the "RV" column in
Gerrit change lists.  Simply "Vote" is an option worth considering,
but it is not clear how "Vote" is different from Code-Review.

Change-Id: Id53d1bea7f53b92009ba6e9274162b8ffa3b2b92
'}]
commit_message:
Use "Rollcall-Vote" for TC and infra-council

Adopt the idea that a review label name should be as
widely-applicable as possible for a given concept so that different
repos with similar needs will end up sharing columns in the user
interface.  Since the TC and infra-specs repos both need "votes from
the people who are members of the committee" as a review label
(while preserving the ability for non-members to leave their feedback
as +/- entries in code-review), have them share the name "Rollcall
Vote".  This will cause them both to appear in the "RV" column in
Gerrit change lists.  Simply "Vote" is an option worth considering,
but it is not clear how "Vote" is different from Code-Review.

Change-Id: Id53d1bea7f53b92009ba6e9274162b8ffa3b2b92

Fetch user token from request rather than env

Use the webob request headers to fetch the user token instead of the
environment variables.

commit_message:
Remove the _msg_format function

The _msg_format plugin was just a way to print out the debug statement
from environment variables. We can do this directly from the user plugin
rather than using env.

Change-Id: I1a8a6a71fcd23eb3da26079264e119a3c29bcb07

Why are we manually managing environment vs headers? We already have a
dependency on webob, let's actually use it and simplify our code a
little.

This is a very basic patch which just allows us to use webob requests
and responses to prove there is no difference. From this we can do
additional cleanups in later reviews.

commit_message:
Base use webob

Why are we manually managing environment vs headers? We already have a
dependency on webob, let's actually use it and simplify our code a
little.

This is a very basic patch which just allows us to use webob requests
and responses to prove there is no difference. From this we can do
additional cleanups in later reviews.

Change-Id: I35c773fb4a15a1c8391c4129300ef2f0592d79ee

I like this.  But I'd really like to push back against a line-length limit.  That can and should be done by humans, not style checkers. 

Altering the code in an example like this just isn't good:
ctrl.label = {
  title: gettext('Key Pair'),
  // jscs:disable maximumLineLength
  subtitle: gettext('A key pair allows you to SSH into your newly created instance. You may select an existing key pair, import a key pair, or generate a new key pair.'),
  // jscs:enable maximumLineLength
  name: gettext('Name'),
  description: gettext('Description'),
  createKeyPair: gettext('Create Key Pair'),
  importKeyPair: gettext('Import Key Pair')
};

Have we gained anything from the jscs comments?"}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-06-04 09:28:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Ref: https://github.com/johnpapa/angular-styleguide#style-y235
"}]
commit_message:
Adding John Papa style guide to JSCS

As we add more javascripts, we need to enforce them. These rules are taken
from JP's website directly. Currently there are 15,406 errors, we need to
address these first before merging this patch. Those are in subsequent patches.

Change-Id: I31d50ead95d502b0463dcd1f378d257b7975e50b
Partially-Implements: blueprint jscs-cleanup
Ref: https://github.com/johnpapa/angular-styleguide#style-y235

commit_message:
Add validate_array to NFS server list

This change adds to https://review.openstack.org/139254 to validate
the value of nfs_shares parameter to ensure it is a valid array before
writing its content into the file referred to by the nfs_shares_config
option.

Change-Id: I40f60ec809e2d4bf69702a2f6dccffdd2001e6d1

There are a handful of job configs that are handled by
other controls on the config form.  We now explicitly
prevent them from showing up in the free entry inputs
while allowing all the unhandled configs to appear when

Change-Id: I493f21500f76bc296c5d41b2b624be335243414f
Closes-Bug: #1445228
'}]
commit_message:
Fixing up how job configs are handled

There are a handful of job configs that are handled by
other controls on the config form.  We now explicitly
prevent them from showing up in the free entry inputs
while allowing all the unhandled configs to appear when
attempting a relaunch of a job.

Change-Id: I493f21500f76bc296c5d41b2b624be335243414f
Closes-Bug: #1445228

commit_message:
fixed behavior for rabbit_hosts variable

We identified an issue where if a user had previously defined rabbit_host,
then went to rabbit_hosts, the old value would cause confusion in many
of the OpenStack tools. This patch ensures that when rabbit_hosts is
defined, rabbit_host is absent, to avoid any configuration problems.

commit_message:
Add configuration helpers for Quobyte

The Quobyte system is conceptionally similar to GlusterFS, which is why
their Cinder driver is forked from the GlusterFS Cinder driver, so I
have taken the same approach here.

Change-Id: I5f207a2ca18bc039ad9d4a6036cec4ad84d5d5f5

commit_message:
Fix object has no attribute debug error

When print_help_if_requested is called, if there is an error,
"object has no attribute 'debug'" gets printed out.  This is
because the parser is passed in to the command rather than the
parsed arguments.

Change-Id: I1863421eff82b3f493d276432369ada9f783b165
Partial-Bug: #1459519

1) This looks like a limited version of auth plugins we already have in ksc. What it does it simply sends ECP wrapped assertions to the SP. Since this looks like a auth plugin (not submodule of a bigger plugin). So I imagine i am going to use it as follows:

# openstack --auth-plugin='k2k' [some params]

This plugin will not allow me to actually fetch assertion from my local Keystone. The news class could be probably used as a sub module doing part of the complex authN.

2) I feel we should add it to python-keystoneclient-federation repo."}, {'account_id': 11022, 'date': '2015-04-13 03:45:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the comments Marek:

1) since it is a plugin that should be "inside" the client itself, I couldn't find any good way to just receive the service_provider id and fetch everything else (which was my first idea)

2) the -federation repo won't have a release and it is being discussed rename it to -saml (major refactoring is needed there, btw - like use the FederationBase class). Since we do not perform any lxml handling in the K2K plugin, KSC is actually a good fit for it.'}, {'account_id': 11022, 'date': '2015-04-13 03:46:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

So i don't have a problem with the code here, but i would like to see some examples of how it's used in practice. Do we expect that a user is going to deal with an ECP assertion? How does the plugin get this assertion from keystone? How do you authenticate to keystone to get the assertion? 

I'm alright if (like saml) we need to have like sub plugins that handle multiple steps - but do you have even a pastebin somewhere with how this would look in user code?"}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2015-04-14 04:38:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Jamie, Rodrigo,

My point was that we should add a complex plugin that can handle all steps, including authn with a local cloud.
This patch can land somehow if you add this class as a subclass that later will be used in a top level plugin. Of course naming etc should be changed.
Also, I don't really support idea of putting it here (instead of python-keystoneclient-federation) just because it doesn't use lxml. To me, a much stronger factor is to put it there as it deals with OS-FEDERATION somehow."}, {'account_id': 11022, 'date': '2015-04-14 19:19:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Marek, I'm for the idea to have all steps being handled in the plugin, but I don't see "how" we can implement? Since a plugin is a client parameter, not the other way around...

Regarding the repo, since -federation won't have releases is a good reason to avoid putting there'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-04-14 22:37:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I think the workflow is very similar to how we do re-scoping today.

1. get a scope Keystone (uuid) token from IdP Keystone
2. *rescope* the token to a given project for a given SP (if the project is known ahead of time). Otherwise, rescope the token to an unscoped token from SP.

Step 2 is consisted multiple steps to be handled by the K2K auth plugin.

1. get a SAML2 token from IdP Keystone for the given SP
2. authenticate to the SP for an unscoped token
3. rescoped the token to a given project if needed'}, {'account_id': 11022, 'date': '2015-04-15 16:29:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Guang, agree with your points. And as I said in previous comments, the first idea was to have a plugin that could receive the sp_id and perform the whole workflow: exchange a token for an assertion and so on...

As I understood correctly, the current ksc design has a "client" that contains a "plugin". To perform the full k2k workflow we'd need the plugin to have a client, so maybe using the current design is the wrong approach? What I mean is... we need a layer that uses the client, not a layer used by the client.'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2015-04-16 00:07:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

it depends, you could have a client return you a plugin like: 

ksc.k2k.get_new_auth(sp_url='', )

i don't know. But forgetting the review for the moment i'd like to know what workflow your aiming for. What do you think is a good user interaction for getting a k2k token?"}, {'account_id': 11022, 'date': '2015-04-16 13:07:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

hmm... was thinking in a workflow like:

1. create a client object authenticated against the Keystone IdP
2. create a k2k plugin passing the sp_id I'm aiming to use
3. pass the plugin to the client
4. get a token from the sp
   4.1. plugin goes to my keystone IdP and asks a SAML assertion for the keystone SP
   4.2. plugin goes to my keystone IdP and do a get_sp(sp_id) to get information like sp_url and sp_auth_url
   4.3. plugin sends SAML assertion to keystone sp (sp_url)
   4.4. plugin gets the unscoped token from keystone sp (sp_auth_url)"}, {'account_id': 11022, 'date': '2015-04-16 13:12:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

for steps like getting the SAML assertion was thinking about using ksc itself: client.federation.saml.create_ecp_assertion(). Instead of making the call using the "session" object that is passed in the get_auth_ref() method.

Does this workflow make sense? What do you think?'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2015-04-21 14:06:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

So you want e.g openstackclient to cover and handle using two authentication plugins:

1) retrieving and samlizing a token
2) bursting into remote clued with my samlized assertion?'}, {'account_id': 11022, 'date': '2015-04-21 15:19:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

no... in the way the plugin is written right now, we would need to perform like you said, in two actions. in the previous comments i described the idea of having a client that would enable the possibility to have it done in a single step in OSC.'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-04-21 17:05:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Those two steps are equivalent to "rescope" if you really look at it at the macro level, rescoping a token from one cloud to another.

What we don't have at the moment, is an aggregated view of the resources. In other words, how do we represent resources across clouds and present them to user at a comprehensive way. But conceptually, the workflow, at the micro level, should be similar to what we have now.

I think the Cisco folks are working on the idea of aggregator in which we'll need to take a closer look at the summit.'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2015-05-02 00:47:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

gyee: It's like rescoping but actually its possibly 2 rescopes and it requires us to figure out how to ask for a normal plugin and then a rescoped plugin, 

We need to figure out how to specify all this information in one go, so that for example OSC can have all the parameters it needs up front. 

I'm guessing it will have to be something like: 

--os-auth-plugin k2k --os-inner-plugin password --os-auth-url XXX .... --os-service-provider XXX --whatever

Then we need to consider how that could possibly clash with existing plugins, like what happens if the --os-inner-plugin is a federation plugin? 

We also need to figure out how this will work in relation to keystoneauth. From what i can see it's going to rely on CRUD from keystoneclient so it will probalby have to continue living here."}, {'account_id': 9981, 'date': '2015-05-07 13:02:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Modify "/v1/{tenant_id}/stacks/{stack_name}/resources" API detail

This patch modifies api-ref[1] for the following REST call detail,
/v1/{tenant_id}/stacks/{stack_name}/resources
It explains for /v1/{tenant_id}/stacks/{stack_name}/resources,
the canonical URL will only be returned for non-deleted stacks,
and the /v1/{tenant_id}/stacks/{stack_name}/{stack_id}/resources
form should be used to fetch the resource list of deleted stacks.

[1] http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-orchestration-v1.html

Closes-Bug: #1460744

Change-Id: I7024193aafe7e7c90a7ac165b23431f469ce6d69

commit_message:
Prevent multiple form submission on table row actions

This disables any table row actions that do a form submit after an
action is taken and the form is being submitted. It also changes the
cursor to make it clear an action is taking place.

Closes-Bug: #1433849
Change-Id: I004f0ae43e5201eba30ff38a34be680416407fbc

commit_message:
Fix wrong assumption of endpoint names

This change comes to fix the wrong assumption that br-storage
and br-mgmt are the storage and management endpoint names,
and instead, use the value of the roles dictionary.

Closes-Bug: #1462005

Change-Id: I53c20fffc7b7a126d448640d23f110751b683abb

commit_message:
Hidden HOST in instance overview page for normal user

If the logined user is normal user, the instance overview page
will always show "HOST: -". There is no need show them for normal
users, it may cause some safety problem.

Closes-Bug: 1417849
Change-Id: Ib51bb05822fe910e97f73af56a8d6856764f7653

[{'created': '2015-02-20 02:07:22.000000000', 'message': "ARP spoofing patch: Ebtables manager

ARP cache poisoning is not actually prevented by the firewall
driver 'iptables_firewall'. We are adding the use of the ebtables
command - with a corresponding ebtables-driver - in order to create
Ethernet frame filtering rules, which prevent the sending of ARP
cache poisoning frames.

The complete patch is broken into smaller patch sets for easier review.

This patch set here includes the ebtables manager class.

Note:
    This commit is based greatly on an original, now abandoned patch,
    presented for review here:

        https://review.openstack.org/#/c/70067/

commit_message:
ARP spoofing patch: Ebtables manager

ARP cache poisoning is not actually prevented by the firewall
driver 'iptables_firewall'. We are adding the use of the ebtables
command - with a corresponding ebtables-driver - in order to create
Ethernet frame filtering rules, which prevent the sending of ARP
cache poisoning frames.

The complete patch is broken into smaller patch sets for easier review.

This patch set here includes the ebtables manager class.

Note:
    This commit is based greatly on an original, now abandoned patch,
    presented for review here:

        https://review.openstack.org/#/c/70067/

Full spec can be found here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/129090/

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: Ic115eeb59cbacdafb85296d435322ea8b8cc99d6
Implements: blueprint arp-spoof-patch-ebtables
Related-Bug: 1274034
Co-Authored-By: jbrendel <jbrendel@cisco.com>

[{'created': '2015-05-09 04:34:46.000000000', 'message': 'Added a new Scheduler, LeastPoolAgentScheduler, which assigns a
pool to an lbaas-agent that has the least number of pools. When
there are multiple lbaas-agents on multiple nodes, pools will be
evenly distributed over the agents. Thus this scheduler helps
the scalability of lbaas-agents serving large number of pools.
At the moment only available lbaas-agent scheduler is ChanceScheduler.

Change-Id: I0b920a8bb5b2918dd5f47ef2a81d3009896af47d

commit_message:
Add a new lbaas agent Scheduler, LeastPoolAgentScheduler

LeastPoolAgentScheduler assigns a pool to an lbaas-agent
with the least number of pools. When there are multiple
lbaas-agents on multiple nodes, pools will be evenly
distributed over the agents. Thus this scheduler helps
the scalability of lbaas-agents serving large number of pools.
At the moment only available lbaas-agent scheduler is ChanceScheduler.

Co-Authored-By: Adam Harwell <flux.adam@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I0b920a8bb5b2918dd5f47ef2a81d3009896af47d

commit_message:
ARP spoofing patch: Ebtables/iptables integration

ARP cache poisoning is not actually prevented by the firewall
driver 'iptables_firewall'. We are adding the use of the ebtables
command - with a corresponding ebtables-driver - in order to create
Ethernet frame filtering rules, which prevent the sending of ARP
cache poisoning frames.

The complete patch is broken into smaller patch sets for easier review.

This patch set here includes the integration between iptables and the ebtables
manager.

Note:
    This commit is based greatly on an original, now abandoned patch,
    presented for review here:

        https://review.openstack.org/#/c/70067/

Full spec can be found here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/129090/

Change-Id: Ibc6d3d520c1383cf7e00f4bdeb7853a41ac4b14b
Implements: blueprint arp-spoof-patch-ebtables
Closes-Bug: 1274034
Co-Authored-By: jbrendel <jbrendel@cisco.com>

I think the general approach is not correct here.
If you have a new agent able to replace two others, we should deprecate central & compute classes and use a new one.
If polling is an agent, it should go to ceilometer::agent::polling new class.
Also, make sure your patch have rspec tests like other classes.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-26 16:36:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add support for ceilometer-polling agent

Add ability to use new ceilometer-polling agent
instead of ceilometer-central, ceilometer-compute or
ceilometer-ipmi. Specify central_namespace, compute_namespace
and ipmi_namespace parameters to set namespaces

Change-Id: I066f601a5234cb689c98e8eea2b5790bdaa5b8b5

commit_message:
Improve unittests for angular charts

Currently our angular charts unit tests are a bit incomplete.

charts.js and chart-tooltip.js don't have any unittests at all.
pie-chart.js has about 2/3rds coverage and 50% branch coverage.

Change-Id: Ibf3667b0d4d0707df7b092053c43bcd70d07bc25
Partial-Bug: 1435869

commit_message:
bump os-client-config to 1.2.0

openstackclient depends on occ version 1.2.0 or newer, as we are
leveraging new functionality from occ.

Change-Id: I51447ffa2b584be65dacf800c65d3b9782592e24

commit_message:
Introduce upper-constraints to requirements.

This is thoroughly documented in the cross project spec 'requirements
management'. In short though, we manage the exact versions we test
with as a change controlled thing and use async processes to push
convergence and keep up to date.

Change-Id: I5fc747646ae9371f0cc085b1e15af45951d20152

Fixes the non-existent exception NoTokenLookupException

Found that troveclient.client raises a non-existent exception,
resolved the same.

Closes-Bug: #1454783

commit_message:
Allow --insecure to override --os-cacert

Change --insecure to ignore the --os-cacert setting.  This is a change
from before where OSC followed the requests pattern of cacert taking
priority.

This logic is also introduced in os-client-config 1.3.0; we
do not require that release yet so it is duplicated here for now.
That change will come with the upcoming global options refactor.

Closes-Bug: #1447784
Change-Id: Iaa6d499ed0929c00a56dcd92a2017487c702774a

their vendor methods. Drivers' own implementations of vendor_passthru()

commit_message:
Don't support deprecated drivers' vendor_passthru

In Kilo, a common mechanism was added that all drivers use for exposing
their vendor methods. Drivers' own implementations of vendor_passthru()
method was deprecated, and backwards compatibility was maintained for any
out-of-tree drivers that still implemented their own version of the
vendor_passthru() method.

This change removes support for that backwards compatibility.

Change-Id: Ib63b0bcc703ad4ea6aeba4e4471baf22e2e1a7fa

commit_message:
Remove dependency on oslo.utils (replace with small util code)

Since this is meant to be a leaf dependency for openstack it should
not depend on any other openstack packages, so to make this happen
just have a really tiny ``_utils.py`` code module that contains the needed
functionality used from ``oslo.utils`` (at a later date we may be able
to better handle this).

Change-Id: Ifbca049f5a56f31ab1ae596d80a5c30ff8438805

[{'created': '2015-06-03 19:57:08.000000000', 'message': 'replace rpc_response_timeout use in rabbit driver

The rabbit driver was using the rpc_response_timeout configuration
option as a reconnect timeout value, even though the option was defined
only in oslo_messaging.client and was not always being registered before
being accessed. An earlier patch fixed this by registering the option
here in the driver, too, but that breaks several levels of
abstraction. This changes the driver to define a new option with the
same default value, so that the driver is only using options it defines
itself. It also removes the old hacky fix.

Closes-bug: #1461182

Change-Id: Ia96c815d157219e12a10d94b87b0156503369a6b
'}]
commit_message:
replace rpc_response_timeout use in rabbit driver

The rabbit driver was using the rpc_response_timeout configuration
option as a reconnect timeout value, even though the option was defined
only in oslo_messaging.client and was not always being registered before
being accessed. An earlier patch fixed this by registering the option
here in the driver, too, but that breaks several levels of
abstraction. This changes the driver to define a new option with the
same default value, so that the driver is only using options it defines
itself. It also removes the old hacky fix.

Closes-bug: #1461182

Change-Id: Ia96c815d157219e12a10d94b87b0156503369a6b

commit_message:
Rename futures.py -> _futures.py and expose at futurist module

Instead of having to expose the underlying futures impl and the
code and modules associated just expose at the futurist module level
the classes we want to expose (to avoid having to expose any inner
module details that people should not be using).

Change-Id: Ib53052a2df5c673b6e0f6956398b56a4f99f93c5

commit_message:
Claim messages and delete messages

Implmenting claim messages and delete messages necessitated a refactoring
of the proxy interfaces. They were ugly and cumbersome. The information
was pushed into the objects. This comes at the expense of a bit of
validation when creating messages but it's minor.

The new design is more in tune with the hypermedia nature of the Message
Service API. Before I was fighting against it, trying to parse out ids.
That's a recipe for brittle code. Much better to make use of the hrefs as
they're intended to be used.

Change-Id: Ib14632a2a05539eae060771f46e0a313a652903f

subject: Create object files directly in datadir.
messages:
[{'account_id': 7578, 'date': '2015-05-07 06:34:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2015-05-07 07:17:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

How's this better than using several tmp directories?  It seems sort of complicated and adds a lot of filesystem operations to the PUT and DELETE paths.

Don't .objtmp files need to be omitted from replication and suffix hashing?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-07 07:21:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

- check-grenade-dsvm http://logs.openstack.org/83/180883/1/check/check-grenade-dsvm/d0f7a07/ : SUCCESS in 37m 32s
- check-swift-dsvm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/83/180883/1/check/check-swift-dsvm-functional/839f21b/ : SUCCESS in 24m 37s'}, {'account_id': 7578, 'date': '2015-05-07 16:47:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Filesystems are optimized for parent-child relationships between directories and files. Doing cross-directory renames breaks the above assumption.

Creating several tmp directories can fix the problem of spreading files across multiple AGs. But it still remains a cross-directory rename.

Creating the objtmp in the actual datadir helps fix the above problem. Creating a symlink to it in the tmp directory just makes it easier to cleanup in case of failures. If there are better ways to fix the failure path, suggestions welcome!

About avoid the .objtmp files during replication: Yes, we should do it and I may have missed that. Can you point me to where in the code this is done?'}, {'account_id': 7578, 'date': '2015-06-04 17:25:10.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-07 06:34:32.000000000', 'message': 'Create object files directly in datadir.

Prior to this change, all object files were initially created in
the "tmp" directory which was created directly under the disk
mount point (e.g. /srv/node/r0/tmp). XFS creates files in the
same allocation group as its parent directory. As a result all files
were getting created in the same allocation group and performance
of XFS dropped significantly very quickly.

This commit fixes the above problem by doing the following:
1. Creates a temperory file with the extension ".objtmp" directly in
   the final data directory.
2. Creates a symlink to this file under the "tmp" directory.
3. If the PUT succeeds, the objtmp file is renamed to .data as earlier
   and the symlink is deleted.
4. If the PUT fails, the object replicator now deletes the symlinks
   as well as any stale .objtmp files.
5. Stale .objtmp files are also deleted while cleaning up the hash
   directory.

Closes-Bug: #1450656.

commit_message:
Create object files directly in datadir.

Prior to this change, all object files were initially created in
the "tmp" directory which was created directly under the disk
mount point (e.g. /srv/node/r0/tmp). XFS creates files in the
same allocation group as its parent directory. As a result all files
were getting created in the same allocation group and performance
of XFS dropped significantly very quickly.

This commit fixes the above problem by doing the following:
1. Creates a temperory file with the extension ".objtmp" directly in
   the final data directory.
2. Creates a symlink to this file under the "tmp" directory.
3. If the PUT succeeds, the objtmp file is renamed to .data as earlier
   and the symlink is deleted.
4. If the PUT fails, the object replicator now deletes the symlinks
   as well as any stale .objtmp files.
5. Stale .objtmp files are also deleted while cleaning up the hash
   directory.

Closes-Bug: #1450656.
Change-Id: I5912f8f523c116c528b216f34f5b7b713c3e6d19

commit_message:
IBP: force signature wiping by lvcreate by '--yes'

By default lvcreate tries to wipe signatures on allocated volume.
If it finds signature, then it will ask for user confirmation to
wipe.
In order to prevent appearing of this interactive prompt '--yes'
should be passed to lvcreate call.

Change-Id: I62bd09d5907e38a457b840acc08a28b487002107
Related-Bug: #1462009

commit_message:
Log with info instead of warn when collector not configured

Users who are debugging unrelated issues are frequently interpreting
logged warnings as an indication that os-collect-config is misconfigured
when the warning is actually harmless.

This change uses info instead of warn for this logging.

Change-Id: I28e0fb37b603364eea72cdc5299a29259489b820
Closes-Bug: #1437952

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-03 20:19:21.000000000', 'message': 'Update erase_node deletion process

When mcollective is launched via Upstart, the current implementation
of the filesystem erase code is not being executed as part of the
SIGTERM handler that is called when we attempt to SIGTERM all
processes. This change pulls the majority of the code we use to
erase a system out of a child thread into the main agent action. This
change leaves the reboot in a child process and SIGTERM handler so
that astute will get the response for the erase_node command and will
mark it complete. An added benefit of this change is that the debug
messages are now returned back to astute and show up in the astute.log
where previously they were being silently discared.

Change-Id: Ib9ee7db0a4d872ea5d1485ec036940f12b0d251e
Closes-Bug: 1461074
'}]
commit_message:
Update erase_node deletion process

When mcollective is launched via Upstart, the current implementation
of the filesystem erase code is not being executed as part of the
SIGTERM handler that is called when we attempt to SIGTERM all
processes. This change pulls the majority of the code we use to
erase a system out of a child thread into the main agent action. This
change leaves the reboot in a child process and SIGTERM handler so
that astute will get the response for the erase_node command and will
mark it complete. An added benefit of this change is that the debug
messages are now returned back to astute and show up in the astute.log
where previously they were being silently discared.

Change-Id: Ib9ee7db0a4d872ea5d1485ec036940f12b0d251e
Closes-Bug: 1461074

commit_message:
Bump keystoneclient version

The openstackclient team is preparing a new release of OSC, and
it will depend on new code that is only available as of
keystoneclient 1.6.0. This will help in migrating devstack to
be fully identity v3 compatible.

Change-Id: I347cae0efe89369f706be0db1bb3b5bca41d3c5f

commit_message:
Add 'to_dict' operation to Resource class

The added 'to_dict()' operation will expose the internal dict of a
Resource object. Users can use this Python dict exposed for further
processing, e.g. create pretty-table on command line, feed fields
extracted to downstream services or tools. The current implementation
filters out the HEADERS in the object.

Change-Id: Ic7b6fb5e6e18311243e537fd76025fcebf7e2ede

subject: Fix cfg.py checks list_config_files if it is empty
messages:
[{'account_id': 14305, 'date': '2015-02-19 17:21:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 14305, 'date': '2015-02-19 17:25:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-02-19 17:39:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

A few nits'}, {'account_id': 14305, 'date': '2015-02-19 17:57:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 14305, 'date': '2015-02-19 17:58:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2015-02-19 18:16:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I don't think this is desirable behavior.  One of the reasons to support a config dir is so distros can provide a place for users to optionally add configs if they want.  Having that place be empty is not necessarily an error, and isn't generally how this sort of thing works in my experience.

I'm -1 on the change, but I'm going to hold off on voting to encourage other reviewers to give their opinions."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-19 19:09:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

To fix a bug in Cinder https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1255354, cfg.py should check if list_config_files is empty because cinder-manage --config-dir is silently ignored if --config-dir exists but doesn't consist config files.
An example command like that exhibits this problem is

su cinder -c 'cinder-manage --config-dir /existing-dir db sync'

where existing-dir is an existing directory which doesn't consist config files"}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2015-02-19 21:46:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

That's not an error from the oslo.config perspective though.  What should happen in that case is the cinder db-sync code should blow up because it won't have the necessary configuration options defined.  The same thing could happen if you specified a config file without the required options, but that's not something oslo.config should care about."}, {'account_id': 14305, 'date': '2015-02-24 10:13:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-24 11:23:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

are not found in the requested directory.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-29 16:06:18.000000000', 'message': 'Make HAProxy check of swift proxy backends via management VIP

W/o this fix, when the management interface on the controller node
running a Swift proxy is down, HAProxy would fail to update
its backend status at the storage network.

This is a problem as we want swift backends not able to connect the
swift endpoint via the management VIP to be marked down. Othewise,
responces time for any requested swift commands would be drastically
longer. Simple httpcheck option cannot resolve this because the swift
healthcheck reports OK, if conntacted via the storage network.

In order to fix this, simple healthcheck script is implemented.
This script is running as xinetid service at TCP port 49001 and
checks the Swift healthcheck report via given swift admin endpoint with
connection timeout 5 seconds and reports an HTTP 200 OK, if the result is OK.
If the result was not OK or the endpoint was not reachable,
it would report an HTTP 503 Error. Expected failover time will
be around 30 seconds.

DocImpact: Reference architecture, swift failover.

Closes-bug: #1459772

Change-Id: I55a35b45257763a20f33bd47cb5c57de53558ccf
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Make HAProxy check of swift proxy backends via management VIP

W/o this fix, when the management interface on the controller node
running a Swift proxy is down, HAProxy would fail to update
its backend status at the storage network.

This is a problem as we want swift backends not able to connect the
swift endpoint via the management VIP to be marked down. Othewise,
responces time for any requested swift commands would be drastically
longer. Simple httpcheck option cannot resolve this because the swift
healthcheck reports OK, if conntacted via the storage network.

In order to fix this, simple healthcheck script is implemented.
This script is running as HTTP xinetid service at TCP port 49001 and
is accessible only from the localhost, 240.0.0.2, and storage plus
management networks. The service verifies the node under check for the:
a) management VIP is pingable via ICMP (by 3 packets)
b) Swift endpoint is reachable by TCP-connect via the local storage address
within 5 seconds connection timeout
c) Swift healthcheck report via the local storage address endpoint is OK

Reports an HTTP 200 OK, if all of the results are OK.
Otherwise, it would report an HTTP 503 Error.
Expected Swift node control plane failover time will be around 30 seconds.
Swift data plane is not affected.

DocImpact: Reference architecture, swift failover.

Closes-bug: #1459772
Related-bug: #1460623

Change-Id: I55a35b45257763a20f33bd47cb5c57de53558ccf
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Pin pyngus version as python-qpid-proton is not in pypi

check-requirements-integration-dsvm is failing with
the following error:

Could not find a version that satisfies the requirement python-qpid-proton<0.10,>=0.9

the latest released version of python-qpid-proton is 0.8.1 at the moment.

Change-Id: I880cffbe003a27e9caba3695e39e39e3bd9b1fcc
(cherry picked from commit 6aa6ddb129b521e1ddbdc203fef557174f1f3b63)

commit_message:
Angular API Unit Tests

Contains tests for API services.  There are currently few of these, so
these are meant to establish a good baseline.  Since many services are
cookie-cutter, the tests often establish a similar structured pattern.

Change-Id: Ice0dd49e61b0c828b502ec7632534732f934ae76
Partial-Bug: 1435869
Closes-Bug: 1449648

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-03 15:25:18.000000000', 'message': 'Removing JobExecutionArgument Table

On implementation of the Unified Job Interface Map story, the
JobExecutionArguments table proved fairly useless. As the
JobExecution object is frozen by the time it gets to the edp
engine, the job_configs json must be updated, and thus no real
record-keeping purpose is served. Removing it for simplicity.

Change-Id: I010290e8c52b016dfa2f4d7563038bd7407563e5
Describes: blueprint unified-job-interface-map
'}]
commit_message:
Removing JobExecutionArgument Table

On implementation of the Unified Job Interface Map story, the
JobExecutionArguments table proved fairly useless. As the
JobExecution object is frozen by the time it gets to the edp
engine, the job_configs json must be updated, and thus no real
record-keeping purpose is served. Removing it for simplicity.

Change-Id: I010290e8c52b016dfa2f4d7563038bd7407563e5
Describes: blueprint unified-job-interface-map

Use oslo.policy instead of incubated version

Corresponding changes were made in murano common policy file
and in requirements.

[{'created': '2015-04-23 15:43:24.000000000', 'message': 'Add Nova scenario to boot multiple servers in one request

The performance profile of, e.g., creating 10 VMs in a single request
is often very, very different from creating 10 VMs in 10 requests, and
the difference only grows with the number of VMs. This adds a scenario
to boot an arbitrary number of servers with a single request, which
can be compared to boot_and_delete_server, which boots them one server
per request.

commit_message:
Add Nova scenario to boot multiple servers in one request

The performance profile of, e.g., creating 10 VMs in a single request
is often very, very different from creating 10 VMs in 10 requests, and
the difference only grows with the number of VMs. This adds a scenario
to boot an arbitrary number of servers with a single request, which
can be compared to boot_and_delete_server, which boots them one server
per request.

Change-Id: I8cb5d6a4f27cce228b83d6a869ed75c505dd6626

commit_message:
More verbose exception when ssh fails

When run deployment create on top of ExistingServers provider,
it's useful to know which host-user-password combination failed.

Change-Id: Ie885375f69502e7dcda257265a8c0c9d785d3ca7

commit_message:
Moved common deprecation code into _DeprecatedBase class

A lot of private code inside @deprecated is not specific to deprecating
a callable, and it will be useful for reuse when we introduce
@deprecated_parameters decorator to deprecate specific parameters, not
the whole callable.

Related-Bug: #1461043
Change-Id: I440f39e2033300f0641b0dbf24ed87533893c141

follows:
1. If an external network is marked as 'shared' then it can be seen and used by
   all tenants
2. When an admin creates an external network, they can use the tenant-id for the

commit_message:
Enable exclusive tenant external network access

Currently all tenants can access all external networks. Currently there is
no way to enable opertaors or admins the ability to provide exclusive tenant
access to external networks.

We add a configuration variable that enables admins to provide the service as
follows:
1. If an external network is marked as 'shared' then it can be seen and used by
   all tenants
2. When an admin creates an external network, they can use the tenant-id for the
   creation. This will enasure that only the tenant can view and use that external
   network.

The above is enabled by the configuration variable 'exclusive_external_networks'

This is by default False to ensure that the existing support is maintained.

WIP

Change-Id: I93901752f87846907874ecce7aa830099c363c0a

commit_message:
Do not automatically target bugs for stable releases

Stable releases should not include all existing closed bugs, so when we
see that the tag is going into a stable branch skip that step and
encourage the user to do the work by hand.

Change-Id: I0bf3df1ea3c49c962eafa00cab797e9dd9c7b6b3

commit_message:
Add "scheduler_use_baremetal_filters" option in nova conf for ironic

This attribute decides whether to use baremetal_scheduler_default_filters or not.
Set the ironic default attributes for True case.

Change-Id: I2c58707140a1e54fb8fdd7627d23aa23f1a236ea
Closes-Bug: #1444860

Sync swift backup files to secondary nodes

This fix syncs swift backups files so it is possible
to replace any controller containing builder files

Look into
http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/content/recover-ring-builder-file.html

commit_message:
New-style page for Liberty-style tracking

Introduce changes as agreed for Liberty release cycle tracking:

- Move the "completed features" to the top of the page
- Move "tracked work in progress" to the bottom
- Use series goal (instead of milestone + priority-set) as the base

commit_message:
Switch to using ostestr for subunit-trace

The subunit-trace module has been moved into the os-testr package.
This decouples the nominally independent module from the rest of
tempest-lib which should enable wider usage. However, since some
packages are depending on tempest-lib to use os-testr at this point
we add it to the requirements.txt file instead of test-requirements
so that those consumers won't be broken when this is release.

Additionally, os-testr includes a testr wrapper, ostestr, which
replaces the pretty_tox.sh script and is used to run unit tests.

Depends-On: Ia399c65e62c2306c9a2d082c6219fcb030b5946b
Change-Id: Iafbfa92a91b945b75aaa1f684594c903c8f6f700

commit_message:
Use correct rbd pool for nova compute

The libvirt option "images_rbd_pool" must refer to the pool for
instances instead of the pool for glance.

Change-Id: Ib384be4e4ee293118c427562d57e01c8de65fdd8

commit_message:
Fixing execution-update API

 * Fixed handling wrong using execution-update
 * Fixed session hanging in case incorrect using execution update API:
     in case of exception neither commit_tx nor rollback_tx has not
     been invoked -> session acquired semaphore but didn't release it.
   Note: it is related only to sqlite (used in unit tests).

Closes-Bug: #1449557

Change-Id: Ic8874b2d498167cac1a88f6d138e8ac0e1d9a67f

commit_message:
Restart netfilter-persistent instead of iptables-persistent

iptables-persistent has merged into netfilter-persitent as a plugin and
/etc/init.d/iptables-persitent is no longer offered on new debians.
This calls the newer variant when it is found and falls back to the old when
it is not.

Change-Id: Ibfc4c0286636633c2b1823aae5885ee6325fec2d

I have added this to the etherpad for the nova unconference in Paris. I'm hoping folks can attend and we can have a good discussion. https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/kilo-nova-summit-unconference"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-11-05 14:42:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

We talked about this in the nova unconference summit session today, but we didn't do a good job of taking notes about what next steps are:

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/kilo-nova-summit-unconference

It sounds like there is at least one thing to do from that (exposing freeze/thaw APIs?), but it's unclear - maybe we need to clear that up on the mailing list?  John Garbutt, Russell Bryant and/or Joe Gordon might have the details in mind.

We talked about writing the freeze/thaw APIs and then an extension to the snapshot API to tell it whether or not the image needs to be frozen before the snapshot.

There was also discussion around policy for server groups but I didn't catch it all, again, probably best rehashed in the mailing list or #openstack-nova channel in IRC (or here!)."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-11-06 01:49:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

I spoke with John Garbutt this afternoon about the result of discussing this at the unconference session and the agreement from the review team was that there was a benefit in adding an API extension to the snapshot API to tell it whether or not to fail the snapshot call if the freeze failed, and that could be done today (and could be implemented across the various drivers).

There was skepticism as to exposing a freeze/thaw API for direct usage. We'd need those details here probably."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-11-24 11:04:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-2

(1 comment)

I don't think we should do this in its current form.

But as Matt mentions, I think its a problem we could/should solve.

My preferred approach is do add ensure_quesced=True to the snapshot API, so snapshot fails if quesce fails.

Then inside the guest, we use the platform specific thing, such as the qemu guest agent, in places where that will work. I don't think its Nova's place to own an in guest agent."}, {'account_id': 13216, 'date': '2014-12-11 20:34:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Thanks John, I'll rework the spec based on this feedback."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-04-10 09:23:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

still -2 on this, given previous comments, but we should also now move to liberty'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-06-04 14:10:33.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This seems to be stalled, free free to restore this though, if thats not correct.'}]

commit_message:
Application Consistent Snapshot

The main goal of blueprint application-consistent-snapshot is to define a hypervisor-agnostic interface
to notify applications of an impending snapshot and to perform any
application-specific quiesce operations prior to a filesystem freeze and
snapshot. A notification is also delivered when a snapshot and thaw have
completed in order for the application to perform any post-thaw operations.

Change-Id: Iaf23d8d3392bf48302bad94f039cf6a307a89f9b

commit_message:
Fix Nova API misimplementation for security groups

The Compute API reference [1] states that the 'description' parameter
is optional when creating a security group. Consequently, omitting this
parameter (or passing an empty string or a whitespace) is allowed.

This patch removes those verifications that should not exist so that
change I404dd30c7dac4b8a9e01cf2ea62fa404fdcce3de can pass Tempest
checks.

[1]: http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-compute-v2-ext.html#createSecGroup

Change-Id: I504f00cecbd004f00b3553e8a23c2b3870405050
Related-Bug: #1434172

commit_message:
horizon/keystone api should use internal_api NW

As most of the OpenStack services are automatically bound
to the public virtual IP already we don't need to set
the default network for Horizon and Keystone to the 'external'
network. These should probably default to the internal_api
network like the rest of the OpenStack services...

Change-Id: I04cf64568c2fc7bb8a821b0de5ba56aa90158e2d

commit_message:
Enforce flake8 E123/6/7/8 in ironic

This patch enforces the rules E123, E126, E127, and E128 in the ironic
code base:

E123 - closing bracket does not match indentation of opening
brackets line
E126 - continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127 - continuation line over-indented for visual indent
E128 - continuation line under-indented for visual indent

This fixes any parts of the current code which fails these rules and
removes these rules from the tox.ini flake8 ignore list.

Change-Id: Ia96582b5e9abc088d6c1694afc93c59be4a4065c
Closes-Bug: 1421522

commit_message:
Add domain record detail screen

This change for the designate dashboard adds a new detail screen
for records.  Previously, the update record screen was used
for this, which is not appropriate in several situations.

Change-Id: I777d8d5f88afb0ad931080648a8ed78c43bfe222
Closes-Bug: #1460729

commit_message:
Add virtual IPs for split out networks

This patch adds VIPs for the internal_api, storage,
and storage management networks.

For puppet these are persisted into a local vip-config
hieradata file which is then used by puppet-tripleo's
loadbalancer module to apply per-service VIP settings.

Change-Id: I909c3bdc9d17a8e15351f4797287769e3f76c849

commit_message:
Add PortName to ports stacks

For VIP ports we set an explicit name on the ports. This
patch adds an optional PortName parameter to the ports
objects which can be used to specify a name.

Change-Id: Iad0f5e4cfc31a931dbb574d9e589570125e9465c

commit_message:
Combine Heat API networks into single net

We probably don't need to split out separate networks
for Heat CFN and Cloudwatch. Just having a single network
for Heat API in the overcloud is probably fine.

Change-Id: I917b314e01227af72129645c9b72ad8e54f07865

commit_message:
Do not raise an exception, Only LOG.
This scenario  is possible that we will get the port status from the
OpenFlow switch before we receive the segmentation_id, when we get the
port/router we will update the snat binding will be updated when we get
the segmentation info

Change-Id: Ifbea11268d5898bd9c59b5a5f6f7494a854af994

commit_message:
Make all-nodes Ip networks configurable

This patch adds a new NetIpListMap abstraction which we can use
to make the all-nodes-config IP list network assignments
configurable. Ip address lists for all overcloud services
which require IPs were added to all-nodes-config so
that puppet manifests can be directly supplied the
correct network list for each service.

Change-Id: I209f2b4f97a4bb78648c54813dad8615770bcf1a

commit_message:
Wire ServiceNetMap as a top level parameter

This patch makes ServiceNetMap a top level parameter.

This is helpful to tools like Tuskar which don't support Heat
environments that contain both a resource_registry and default_parameters.

ServiceNetMap will in fact be utilized at the top level in some of
the VIP related patches that follow.

Change-Id: I375063dacf5f3fc68e6df93e11c3e88f48aa3c3a

commit_message:
Do not loop on the router class do the loop on the tenant subnet class c
for fast access.
Separate patch will handle this duplicate data structure, use only net
ids in the router object

Change-Id: Id98c527608cc21bddb7aa07c59c5857c3e465510

subject: subnets data was added to the port object sent on RPC for add_arp and del_arp BUT  were not added to the get_ports_by_subnet. So on startup when we actively requested the port in the l3 controller agent we got the port data but with missing inforamtion. Added the same subnets data to the ports object when get is called

commit_message:
subnets data was added to the port object sent on RPC for
add_arp and del_arp BUT  were not added to the get_ports_by_subnet.
So on startup when we actively requested the port in the l3 controller
agent we got the port data but with missing inforamtion.
Added the same subnets data to the ports object when get is called

Change-Id: I9d132fab16eb29d4d76b52f3120fc8d7f637b704

The problem is now that the aggregation method has diverged so much it no longer works against mongodb. The test cases are now need to run against db2 nosql, not mongodb.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-11-14 09:24:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

are you going to proposed to infra to add db2nosql gate? i guess a followup would be, do you or ibm still intend on supporting this driver... we're starting to notice the code is diverging a bit and we're having to add mongodb specific tests because db2 driver is lagging."}, {'account_id': 7729, 'date': '2014-11-14 11:50:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Little note.'}, {'account_id': 10987, 'date': '2014-11-14 13:58:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Little nit is inline, thank you for the patch.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-01-28 14:42:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So this change won't work with MongoDB, so you'd really have to test a DB2 storage driver against a DB2 nosql backend, which we don't have running in the community, the tests running with the DB2 storage driver just run with the MongoDB backend (I'm catching up on all of this now, not a ceiometer guy really :) ).

Would it be reasonable to look at alternative testing strategies for the DB2 storage driver, i.e. only run with that if CEILOMETER_TEST_DB2_URL points to something that works, else skip?

It sounds like the HBase backend only works locally right now, at least until https://review.openstack.org/#/c/86683/ is merged, but that's a devstack change so would be an integration test pipeline, i.e. tempest, right?  That wouldn't be for running unit tests.

So I'd be proposing that long with this change there is a change to how the DB2 backend works in the tests and skips if there isn't a real DB2 nosql backend connection available.

I'd think then we'd be looking at 3rd party CI or something, but at least that would decouple the changes to the mongodb code that Gordon mentioned since this driver was lagging behind in some functionality (which this change does help to close that gap)."}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-06-04 13:28:00.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

a birdy told me to abandon -- see http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-dev/%23openstack-dev.2015-06-04.log.html'}]

added description column in firewall tables

commit_message:
Add system tests for the InfluxDB-Grafana plugin

This change adds tests for the InfluxDB-Grafana plugin [1].
We are testing the deployment in multi-node with HA with the plugin and
we are checking that:
  - InfluxDB server is responding
  - Grafana is running
  - OSTF test suite is executed without errors

[1] https://github.com/stackforge/fuel-plugin-influxdb-grafana

Change-Id: Ib5c37fa57c8bb674fc709ff2336ce97f12982b8a
Closes-Bug: #1453737

commit_message:
Remove IPv4AddressType validate function in magnum

Since magnum has bumped up WSME to 0.7, and IPv4AddressType validate
problem has been fixed in this version, so I think it's the time to
remove the IPv4AddressType validate workaround in magnum.

Change-Id: I1f982b56a0ac41d4d6c50b2cbf8fa4162a709dc1
Closes-Bug: #1461392

commit_message:
devstack: Add pre_test_hook.sh.

Add a pre_test_hook.sh script to be used by our tempest CI job.  This
will let us tweak the regex used to select which tempest tests run by
updating this file instead of updating the job definition in the
project-config repo.

Change-Id: Id2f4b325dd8ca852f7b02f9654f53f0982647ea7
Depends-on: I770111bb5f9818343e640edc7d590813e5dee9bf
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Streamline setting MURANO_REPO_URL

Murano devstack integration plugin uses MURANO_REPOSITORY_URL to set
MURANO_REPO_URL. This commit updates murano-integration script to use
appropriate variable and streamlines the whole procedure, by setting
sensible default.

Change-Id: Ifc38a4b4ae88fcf2f32929fe57c4a0c46f434513

'}, {'created': '2015-06-02 05:50:28.000000000', 'message': 'Fix list of OVS tunnel_types available

The list of tunnel_types available in OVS does not have to
match the list of allowed tunnel_types in ML2. Not all values
are valid for both settings. See [1] and [2].

This change configures OVS for GRE and VXLAN tunneling, still
subject to NeutronEnableNetworkTunnelling param.

Also passes NeutronEnableTunnelling to controllers, which
previously was mistakenly only passed to computes.

1. https://github.com/stackforge/puppet-neutron/blob/master/manifests/agents/ml2/ovs.pp#L49
2. https://github.com/stackforge/puppet-neutron/blob/master/manifests/plugins/ml2.pp#L32

Change-Id: I74756732deabd1c7ba9039832ea169fd322a569f

commit_message:
Pass NeutronEnableTunnelling to controllers

We forgot to pass NeutronEnableTunnelling param to controllers
(passed only to computes), making it unusable.

Change-Id: I74756732deabd1c7ba9039832ea169fd322a569f

Ruby and all,

I couldn't attend yesterday's Ironic Official IRC meeting.
So I've read the minutes.

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/ironic/2015/ironic.2015-06-01-17.00.log.html

And then somehow it really urged me to make comment here :)

I vote "Yes", because PEP8 is a standard to work with many developers. I think PEP8 is not perfect, but improving PEP8 is another topic, I personally think It should not be mixed and discussed separately.

We have all different backgrounds and cultures.
I'm really respect with each individuals' choice.
What I really interested in is each individual's reason of his/her choice.
Especially I really would like to know Ruby's reason of voting "No".

Because without knowing the reason, we cannot deepen our discussion.

Best regards,

commit_message:
Remove E123/6/7/8 from flake8 ignore list

This is the final peice of a larger effort to fix and enforce the
rules E123, E126, E127, and E128 in the ironic code base:

E123 - closing bracket does not match indentation of opening
brackets line
E126 - continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127 - continuation line over-indented for visual indent
E128 - continuation line under-indented for visual indent

This patch removes these rules from the tox.ini flake8 ignore list.

Change-Id: I6f6f86d59ea391cb14b13c1e37bfc3e45512ef7d
Partial-Bug: 1421522

commit_message:
Fix flake8 E123/6/7/8 in ironic/api

This is a section of a larger effort to fix and enforce the rules
E123, E126, E127, and E128 in the ironic code base:

E123 - closing bracket does not match indentation of opening
brackets line
E126 - continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127 - continuation line over-indented for visual indent
E128 - continuation line under-indented for visual indent

Change-Id: I428f2b2c0a23c769164cbd19de36f146d3f90be2
Partial-Bug: 1421522

commit_message:
Fix flake8 E123/6/7/8 in ironic /cmd /db and /dhcp

This is a section of a larger effort to fix and enforce the rules
E123, E126, E127, and E128 in the ironic code base:

E123 - closing bracket does not match indentation of opening
brackets line
E126 - continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127 - continuation line over-indented for visual indent
E128 - continuation line under-indented for visual indent

Change-Id: Ie6913b36482cfeaf55fe9bc6bb067069c35631b3
Partial-Bug: 1421522

commit_message:
Fix flake8 E123/6/7/8 in ironic/common

This is a section of a larger effort to fix and enforce the rules
E123, E126, E127, and E128 in the ironic code base:

E123 - closing bracket does not match indentation of opening
brackets line
E126 - continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127 - continuation line over-indented for visual indent
E128 - continuation line under-indented for visual indent

Change-Id: I2a15b13d2c171b70d8e94ff11d89eba27da8ebb2
Partial-Bug: 1421522

commit_message:
Fixes flake8 E123/6/7/8 in ironic/conductor

This is a section of a larger effort to fix and enforce the rules
E123, E126, E127, and E128 in the ironic code base:

E123 - closing bracket does not match indentation of opening
brackets line
E126 - continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127 - continuation line over-indented for visual indent
E128 - continuation line under-indented for visual indent

Change-Id: I2b621da7914216464e27344b5e585868ad1262b6
Partial-Bug: 1421522

commit_message:
Fixes flake8 E123/6/7/8 for ironic/drivers

This is a section of a larger effort to fix and enforce the rules
E123, E126, E127, and E128 in the ironic code base:

E123 - closing bracket does not match indentation of opening
brackets line
E126 - continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127 - continuation line over-indented for visual indent
E128 - continuation line under-indented for visual indent

Change-Id: I81f44f649fa5408081d26535a2617ed550c617bb
Partial-Bug: 1421522

commit_message:
Fix flake8 E123/6/7/8 for ironic/tests/api

This is a section of a larger effort to fix and enforce the rules
E123, E126, E127, and E128 in the ironic code base:

E123 - closing bracket does not match indentation of opening
brackets line
E126 - continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127 - continuation line over-indented for visual indent
E128 - continuation line under-indented for visual indent

Change-Id: I74b33ecabe3f173268bc77ea94dd3d349e779294
Partial-Bug: 1421522

commit_message:
Fix flake8 E123/6/7/8 in non-driver ironic/tests

This is a section of a larger effort to fix and enforce the rules
E123, E126, E127, and E128 in the ironic code base:

E123 - closing bracket does not match indentation of opening
brackets line
E126 - continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127 - continuation line over-indented for visual indent
E128 - continuation line under-indented for visual indent

Change-Id: I8a7bb0c2a8fe58117d0a0ac352e130fd4819f2ac
Partial-Bug: 1421522

[{'created': '2015-02-12 12:57:43.000000000', 'message': "Allowing reading from object body on download

Currently, get_object returns a generator. This allows access to the
object's data in multiples of 'resp_chunk_size'.

This patch adds a read function to also allow accessing the object data
using read(size).

This allows, for example, the consumer of an object (where no byte range
has been specified) to read up to certain boundaries while streaming to
a new Large Object with segments of a specified size.

Change-Id: I1cfb67f45afc7015fd896f1a89bebae048871769

commit_message:
Allow reading from object body on download

Currently, get_object returns a generator. This allows access to the
object's data in multiples of 'resp_chunk_size'.

This patch adds a read function to also allow accessing the object data
using read(size).

This allows, for example, the consumer of an object (where no byte range
has been specified) to read up to certain boundaries while streaming to
a new Large Object with segments of a specified size.

Reading and chunking can be safely mixed.

Related-Bug: 1367925
Co-Authored-By: Clay Gerrard <clay.gerrard@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I1cfb67f45afc7015fd896f1a89bebae048871769

\x0318\x08<\x08cdent\x0318\x08>\x08\x0f I think that we should not enable pagination as a signal to people that they should make more restricted queries

commit_message:
Add Mysql pagination for resource, meter and sample

This patch add the pagination query of meter, resource and sample,
includes:

* implement of pagination query of ceilometer API layer
* implement the definition of common pagination model in storage base
* implement utility methods used to transform pagination parameters base
  on sqlalchemy models definitions
* implement the pagination query of meter, resource and sample of
  sqlalchemy

Partially implements: blueprint ceilometer-events-pagination
Change-Id: I8f04433d835789cbbc31a85e5a5ba0386afb29ff

commit_message:
Remove pypy tox target

pypy+gnocchi is a non-starter because no numpy for pypy. Having this
present as a default tox target causes noisy errors on a machine
where pypy is installed, so for sake of cleanliness it's now gone.

Change-Id: I05aea72721d03255e0f224ec5b910a26a287eb5b

commit_message:
Add the Hook Point API

Hook points allow installing a package that provide a decorator for some
function / method. The intent is to use it for organization specific
code.

The sample config contains an example.

See: https://review.openstack.org/171689/
Implements: blueprint hook-point-api
Change-Id: If98d9450cfd6b1a2a3cb23d8bc51940c1b6ee37a

commit_message:
Don't set OVSDHCPINTERFACES if bridge is static

Updates the ifcfg provider so that we don't set
the OVSDHCPINTERFACES config setting if
the interface is private. This doesn't seem to cause
any functional issues but it is not required
and can be confusing.

Change-Id: I9d51905df87969ae1b221680e8f0b5befc7b6bfe

Get rid of oslo-incubator copy of middleware

We have already moved away from openstack/common/middleware modules
to the oslo_middlware library. Let us cleanup the remaining files
here.

[{'created': '2015-05-29 12:32:24.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Do not cache number of CPUs of the hypervisor

The number of CPUs on a compute node can vary during the runtime of
the nova compute service due to CPU hotplug events. For example
an administrator can add or remove CPUs based on the current
resource consumption.

As a result, the number of CPUs should not be cached within
the nova service, but it needs to be retrieved again when
updating resource allocation to report it to the controller
node.

Change-Id: I2382a22c7aa492071647fa6dca42b54d1baf050d
Closes-bug: #1460043
'}]
commit_message:
libvirt: Do not cache number of CPUs of the hypervisor

The number of CPUs on a compute node can vary during the runtime of
the nova compute service due to CPU hotplug events. For example
an administrator can add or remove CPUs based on the current
resource consumption.

As a result, the number of CPUs should not be cached within
the nova service, but it needs to be retrieved again when
updating resource allocation to report it to the controller
node.

Change-Id: I2382a22c7aa492071647fa6dca42b54d1baf050d
Closes-bug: #1460043

Add node UUID to response from /v1/continue

This patch modifies the _process_node function's return value to ensure
that it always includes the nodes UUID.

Closes-Bug: #1460689

commit_message:
Get rid of network bonds with 'balance-*' modes

Since it was decided to move 'balance-tlb' and 'balance-alb'
bonding modes to experimental features (see bug #1458935),
there is no need to run tests with them as they expectedly
fail. But we still need to check bonding feature with all
supported network types, so switch bonding mode to
'active-backup' in all tests.

Change-Id: Id75f8b17a28dc8da27ca4b4ff8e3ceb1fee69d83
Partial-bug: #1319413

commit_message:
[Murano Docs] Remove old versions of articles

As the draft folder now contains the following articles:
- MuranoPL: Murano Programming Language
- MuranoPL Core Library
- Dynamic UI definition specification
- Murano package repository
this patch removes them in order not to confuse users.
Also removes the /doc/source/murano_pl folder.

Change-Id: I294d0b391c3d19af185427a8c9b0c0d742e1f2de

commit_message:

Adds the Note to the top of the landing page informing the user
that the documentation is under development at the moment.
The link in this note leads to the new docs structure.

commit_message:
Add 'docker' to the list of known hypervisor types

nova-docker is out of tree, but it's starting to be used by people, and
being able to use a docker-specific hypervisor type can be quite useful
(in mixed-hypervisor environments, for instance).

Change-Id: I5a50de6bf73372f1ab999fd977aa58b33ffacfb9

commit_message:
ifcfg: don't set VLAN=yes if is an ovs_port

When using the ifcfg provider vlans on bridges (or bonds)
fail to startup correctly. This is because VLANs on an OVS
bridge are configured as internal ports and these should not
have the VLAN=yes or PHYSDEV ifcfg settings specified.

Change-Id: Ieb743eda8f0a25cdaca43bdea767af26bf504f15

commit_message:
Sync builder files for swift to secondary nodes

This fix syncs builder files so it is possible
to replace any controller containing builder files

Look into
http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/content/recover-ring-builder-file.html

commit_message:
Take into account nodes which require redeployment

_check_nodes_are_online should take into account that some nodes
may require redeployment and raise an error if such nodes are not online.

Change-Id: I7b2638c148fb690f3c7c9097e2a809cdfc3a649e
Closes-Bug: #1461136

Murano docs: Intro, key features, target users

1. Adds Intro to the index page.

2. Adds the 'Key features' article to the 'Introduction'
   section.

3. Adds the 'Target users' article to the 'Introduction'
   section.

commit_message:
Speed up message expiration tests

Speed up the message expiration tests by checking the mongo gc more
often instead of sleeping 60 seconds by default. This also allows using
the ttlMonitorSleepSecs in mongo to reduce the gc interval.

Change-Id: I6f83a76181204f14711a426037dde231ffe97e95

commit_message:
Clarify code comment in Redis backend

I noticed this says to skip *unclaimed* messages when in fact it skips
claimed ones.

Change-Id: I2173f5c8bc8cadb4dcb58e612c774acbfaa86d5b

commit_message:
Encrypt properties data

Encrypt properties data before storing it in database and decrypt it
when the resource is being loaded from the database.

Change-Id: I646542b1d03296f62a83041dc2a0ca2719775289
Implements: blueprint encrypt-hidden-parameters

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: I35ac53ec8a51ef0037c81aa939b871c9d037272d

Remove iso8601 dependency

Ceilometer does not import and use this module directly, no need to list
it in the requirements.

Change-Id: I6ffd0762677c28eaeef8a110a9af3528cac61ebf

commit_message:
Switch get_all_snapshots to use objects

The following patch switches direct db calls in
volume/api.py get_all_snapshots to use SnapshotList
instead.

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-objects
Change-Id: Ifdccc81a087f9797fcfbf098d3ecea3875ad7bd9

commit_message:
Add support for missing features in zaqarclient v1.1

Python-zaqarclient currently has some missing features that
need to be added. This spec describes which endpoints are missing and
how those are going to be added to the client side.

Change-Id: Ic58ab9bd9c2f167e9f60e489a05744dbf87741a8
