commit_message:
Adding config-like auth configuration for functional tests

Using config file generation in post_test_hook.sh and using this
file for autorizing the muranoclient in functioanl tests if
global variables not injected into.

Change-Id: Ib3a1dbf2d9978cc1bf786010c21c41a8a65d9da9
Closes-Bug: #1461096

commit_message:
change some ml2 log level to error

The previous log level this patch trying to change
are warning and debug, they will be logged when
binding between ports and hosts failed, in dead ovs
agent or bridge mappings dismatch cases.

When these issues happened, neutron server can still
working, but these issues will stop neutron from
providing basic network service. So it makes sense
to become ERROR level. And aslo, the previous log
level couldn't help user to quickly locate root reason
in neutron log, when booting instance failed, and in
nova compute log, "Unexpected vif_type=binding_failed"
can be found and it's an obvious network error.

Change-Id: I232d3634cadcffa64e50a79197ba35db2ad90dbd
Closes-Bug: #1460491

rpc: clean JSON serializer, remove strtime() usage

strtime() is going to be deprecated in oslo_utils, see
I8b5119e64369ccac3423dccc04421f99912df733.

Change-Id: Ie34619d0c2c5db90d1bc34530a027884c6b124db

 >>> maybe_port = 0

 3306

Is that correct?"}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-06-03 21:06:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks Kobi for the change looks ok.'}, {'account_id': 13438, 'date': '2015-06-04 02:25:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Joshua not really.
Port 0 is a reserved port for TCP and not usable by applications such as mysql.

commit_message:
Use MySQL default port when not set explicitly

When a port number is not set explicitly in the connect URL to MySQL,
use MySQL default port number 3306

OperatorClouds.

commit_message:
Change time check and sync procedure on Ceph nodes

  Add fuelweb_test.checkers.ceph module which aggregates all Ceph related
  handlers and checkers.
  Additional logic is provided to check time consistency of Ceph cluster.
  Before checking Ceph health status, the test checks a time skew and tries to
  sync time on inconsistent nodes.
  Fix time logging format in ntp.py.

Change-Id: I5f31785fa4d9b3adc9f1f0354bc24431745f115a
Closes-Bug: #1393473

commit_message:
Replace lock_utils lock(s) with fasteners package

The usage of this package allows us to get rid of the
reader/writer lock (since that package provides that) as well as
the interprocess lock as all of these are now provided by that
package instead.

Change-Id: I87990b46d397f6df779de7028bcc40e28621e1ba

commit_message:
Don't query db if criteria longer than col length

When a long query parameter name is used (such as a name with
more than 255 characters), this is never going to match a user
in the SQL backend, because names can only be up to 255
characters. Keystone doesn't have to bother querying the backend
in these cases and doing so is unnecessary. With this change,
these types of requests are short-circuited.

Some databases (e.g., DB2) return an error if the query string is
longer than the field.

Change-Id: I68b3abaabec6cb46a9a320e312c0be7707009170
Closes-Bug: #1386773

commit_message:
I/O (PCIe) based NUMA scheduling

This feature will add support for intelligent NUMA node placement for
guests that have been assigned a hosts PCI device, avoiding unnecessary
memory transactions.

Implements blueprint input-output-based-numa-scheduling

Previously-approved: juno

Co-Authored-By: Adrian Hoban <adrian.hoban@intel.com>

Change-Id: I80b9b8aea7f7395070b01ca8c520ee3c078c5df1

thanks'}, {'account_id': 11592, 'date': '2014-08-25 23:07:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-09-08 23:33:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-10-04 22:59:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 5623, 'date': '2014-10-06 15:04:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

As posted on the original bug:


"I don't agree with the direction of this bug. Horizon as constructed now blocks render until all the data is collected from the APIs and the page is sent from the server to the client. When horizon is used in a production environment, where API calls can take on the order of seconds, this causes the user to click a navigation link and see no action other than hopefully an obscure loading icon from the browser. The purpose of the spinner is to indicate, your action requests has been acknowledged and is being processed. The spinner should be visible on all panels (not just Identity) that take any measurable time to load.

If the spinner is actually not showing up for the instances page when necessary, that would be the bug. But I imagine, you are using this in devstack where the load times are minimal and you are only seeing the spinner because keystone APIs are slower to respond."'}, {'account_id': 9622, 'date': '2014-10-07 00:22:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

hi! when we had identity panels as part of admin, they did not show the loading... so not sure what makes it different now?

Feel free to reactivate the review by pressing the restore button and leaving a 'recheck' comment to get fresh test results."}, {'account_id': 16674, 'date': '2015-06-04 07:37:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think that the fix is incomplete. To satisfy the original specification (showing loading for all panels) mentioned by David Lyle. Either panel under a dashboard or panel group should display a spinner when clicked.
Suggestion 1:
  // panel selection
  $('.nav_accordion > dd > ul > li > a, .nav_accordion > dd > div > ul > li > a').click(function() {
    horizon.modals.modal_spinner(gettext("Loading"));
  });

Suggestion 2:
    // panel selection
  $('.nav_accordion > dd ul > li > a').click(function() {
    horizon.modals.modal_spinner(gettext("Loading"));
  });'}]

commit_message:
Make the number of green threads configurable

The patch makes the number of green threads configurable by creating a
global eventlet GreenPool, and providing the function utils.spawn_n as a
proxy to create threads using the pool. The total number of threads
available in the pool is configurable through the new max_threads config
option.

Change-Id: Id62ca6a2fc342de0514c6a88af8bebbe94d86dbc
Closes-Bug: #1419736

commit_message:
Add an extension section to the developer docs.

This extension section provides guidance for deployers wanting to add
their own services and configuration to os-ansible-deployment.

This documentation also includes some recommendations for how projects
sourcing os-ansible-deployment might be structured.

Change-Id: I7ddac9ff2cab8b5a7cb9af1ba6bb3bdde64d60ea
Implements: blueprint developer-docs
(cherry picked from commit 0ec7f7d850c2f6425ea56724b9d702011868c124)

commit_message:
Allow configuration of Keystone SQLAlchemy options

Add variables for the following 3 keystone.conf vars:
- max_overflow (default 10)
- max_pool_size (default 5)
- pool_timeout (default 30)

This allows for sql tuning to better support bulk operations
(boot/delete) with the ability to define custom values in 
keystone.conf based on business needs.

based on commit 58212d9b8a7e692d49ae2852f349829355f93a2b
Closes-Bug: #1460751
Change-Id: I59bb32ed2edc9a5f026b7e674dab851376a1f20a

[{'created': '2015-05-21 01:09:42.000000000', 'message': "Modularizing Neutron playbooks

Added modularization for neutron setup in juno branch.

- Core Plugin can be selected by name, and new ones added to the
  'plugins_neutron' data structure
- Agents are enabled/disabled through 'services_neutron' dict
  in group_vars/neutron_all.yml
- Playbooks for agents are run based on individual enbaled status
- Agent service names propagate to appropiate handlers

Implements: blueprint modularize-neutron-plays

Change-Id: I65c6ccaa35c8181a5df4cdccddae68c7b307fdf5

Added modularization for neutron setup in juno branch.

- Core Plugin can be selected by name, and new ones added to the
  'plugins_neutron' data structure
- Agents are enabled/disabled through 'services_neutron' dict
  in group_vars/neutron_all.yml
- Playbooks for agents are run based on individual enbaled status
- Agent service names propagate to appropiate handlers

- Patch4: removed neutron-agent from services

commit_message:
Modularizing Neutron playbooks

Added modularization for neutron setup in juno branch.

- Core Plugin can be selected by name, and new ones added to the
  'plugins_neutron' data structure
- Agents are enabled/disabled through 'services_neutron' dict
  in group_vars/neutron_all.yml
- Playbooks for agents are run based on individual enbaled status
- Agent service names propagate to appropiate handlers

- Patch5: removed neutron-agent from services
- Patch6: namespaced parameter names to neutron

Implements: blueprint modularize-neutron-plays

Change-Id: I65c6ccaa35c8181a5df4cdccddae68c7b307fdf5
Signed-off-by: Javeria Khan <javeriak@plumgrid.com>

commit_message:
Update for pip 7.0.0

The trusted host option when installing from a domain that is not
https is no longer optional. This change adds a domain variable to
the groupvars/all.yml and ensures that the get-pip.py installation
process is using the `--trusted-host`` flag and is pointed back at
the domain name used in the "openstack_upstream_domain".

Change-Id: I18539cf4b8790c096d44a0de4985b9d4293d95e3

commit_message:
Restart Apache when Keystone configuration changes

Currently, when a change occurs in a Keystone configuration file it's not
taking effect since the Apache service is not being notified to restart.

Merge the keystone_apache role with the keystone_common role to take
advantage of the existing Restart Apache handler with tasks that
make changes to Keystone configuration files.

Change-Id: If7bbe23688bbc0565e43a74103a9d9ce89a82236
Closes-Bug: #1457737

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-23 11:40:01.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid keeping re-downloading container caches

When the cache tarball gets deleted at the end the task set in
playbooks/roles/lxc_hosts/tasks/lxc_cache.yml
then it will be downloaded again at subsequent runs, which makes the
download task not idempotent, and needlessly slow.

The unarchive task also needs to only be executed if the download task
performed a change.

Change-Id: I4e433e82499f5cfa0b5dde44a6aa7bab113d9e0e

commit_message:
Avoid keeping re-downloading container caches

When the cache tarball gets deleted at the end the task set in
playbooks/roles/lxc_hosts/tasks/lxc_cache.yml
then it will be downloaded again at subsequent runs, which makes the
download task not idempotent, and needlessly slow.

The unarchive task also needs to only be executed if the download task
performed a change.

Ensure that the location the download is placed and the directory it's extracted
to are different.

Change-Id: I4e433e82499f5cfa0b5dde44a6aa7bab113d9e0e

commit_message:
run-upgrade.sh: add a missing redirect

When adding rabbit_cluster_name: rpc to the user variables, it just
echoed it and did not redirect the output to add it to the
user_variables.yml file.

Change-Id: Idddc9eedf868f1312d7a449bba7079d207309538

commit_message:
Add Sphinx machinery and initial docs.

This commit gets the doc directory and Sphinx configuration started.

Further documentation will depend on the Sphinx files and the index.rst
file at the very least.

The dev-requirements were updated to install Sphinx, and a gating script
was added to do the building for when we move to actually do gating on
the docs. The docs gate script is currently set to treat warning as
errors.

Change-Id: I977a2e53f1b0981cbc702ac53f2198d9f6a9da9d
Implements: blueprint developer-docs
(cherry picked from commit 9012a748d3656e91a15709d6a0a0c8fb22098fc8)

commit_message:
timeutils: fix newer/older comparison with TZ aware datetime

Blindly replacing the timezone information from a timestamp does not
make it correctly UTC. It just strips information away, and therefore
does not make any valid comparison.

This fixes the comparison function by normalizing the timestamps to UTC
before doing any comparison.

Change-Id: I3a1b1eae497200ca951ccb003dbcc75fb75380fa

commit_message:
Password is not strong enough failures

Add a method to generate password with
1: use of both upper- and lower-case letters (case sensitivity)
2: inclusion of one or more numerical digits
3: inclusion of special characters, e.g. @, #, $ etc.
4: at least 15 characters in length

Closes-Bug: 1448217

Change-Id: I86bf157f1bdb44f5fc579dc5317784fe31df8521

commit_message:
Tolerate iso style timestamps for cells rpc communication

There's been an effort in oslo to use iso date/time stamps
over the wire (including this change for example -
I262391987d25b483d2bec4ac3abe94b6e9d032ad)

So we should be able to convert both the old and the
new style date/time stamps and store them in our
database. Without this change if we run nova dsvm
cells tests against oslo.* master, we see failures.

If we don't fix tolerate the different styles of
date/time stamp strings, next update of the oslo
libraries will break Nova cells.

Change-Id: Ib7e60ed94edd1eb409baf8c29c61237d85944787

commit_message:
Move unlock_override policy enforcement into V2.1 REST API layer

Commit 01be083 misses unlock_override policy check in V2.1 REST API layer.

This patch fixes this bug and adds related unittest.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part
Closes-Bug: 1429126

Change-Id: Ie5481267d0631fae7f413e63ae6c38656d3ca933

commit_message:
Replace parse_strtime with parse_isotime in older/newer

There's no reason to limit parsing to strtime format as isotime format
is better and than parsing isotime also parses strtime formatted
strings.

Change-Id: I94dc4e9fa08b10139e3ef27fa94e33e0aa124110

commit_message:
Use oslo_config choices support

The oslo_config library supports the choices keyword argument. This commit
leverages the use of choices for StrOpts in Nova's configuration.

This change also adds 'ploop' as a valid value for the images_type option.
This was previously a valid value, but not documented.

Closes-Bug: #1423973

Change-Id: I4c0eb1366cc8a1b001fd403b67c3eec11f831541

can we do same thing to common code?'}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-04-02 03:12:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Yes, @jichenjc, like you say, adding _record_action_start is really alternatives, and I think about it before, but only a issue exist. The init_instance is recovery workflow for broken action, like: powering_off, powering_of, rebooting, unpausing, so I think that we should use the original action record to finish the action, the records of instance_actions and instance_actions_events would be consistence and consequent. If we add _record_action_start and use new instance_action record to continue the workflow, the original instance_action would be unfinished, and no event record.'}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2015-04-02 08:01:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Take this example 

1863     def force_stop(self, context, instance, do_cast=True, clean_shutdown=True):
1864         LOG.debug("Going to try to stop instance", instance=instance)
1865
1866         instance.task_state = task_states.POWERING_OFF
1867         instance.progress = 0
1868         instance.save(expected_task_state=[None])
1869
1870         self._record_action_start(context, instance, instance_actions.STOP)

if crash between 1868 and 1870 , I think the 
previous action will not be recorded and you code will still
 fail? 

so we can't guarantee the correctness here'}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-04-02 12:09:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I get your point, but I think it occurs only in theory or very rare case. Actually the instance fall in powering_off task state, because the nova-compute shutdown or reboot when the instance execute a long-duration action, like: graceful shutdown, at that time the action record should be ready, this patch work in the case.

And if follow your suggestion, how we deal with the issue of no event action? like I say in last comments.'}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2015-04-02 12:34:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Fix failure of stopping instances during init host

When nova-compute restart, the context was generated again in
init_host workflow, the request_id was different with the request_id
recorded in InstanceAction, so we can't get the original record
according to request_id. Try to get the last one so that
init_instance can continue to finish the recovery action, like:
powering_off, unpausing, and so on.

The instance fails in powering_off task state, because the nova-compute
shutdown or reboot when the instance execute a long-duration action,
like: graceful shutdown, at that time the action record should be ready.

Change-Id: Ib84bd7419eac57da56c1a9a1c44cc63d2600f1ba
Closes-Bug: #1435198

commit_message:
Add retry to iSCSI delete

Looks like there might be a race in trying to delete
a target immediately after a logout.  I've seen this
a couple times in my CI system this week, but it
certainly doesn't seem at all prevalent.

This patch just adds a simple retry with delay that should
take care of any race issues here.

Also addressed some pep8 violations while touching the file.

Change-Id: I7a57687cac311c5e53361ccbceb1addb419f1e9f
Closes-Bug: 1324670

commit_message:
Add volume ID to fake volumes in Gluster tests

This adds the volume ID field to the fake volume objects
in the GlusterFS tests.  Turning up concurrency exposes some
issues where access of this field is attempted but doesn't
exist.

Parital-Bug: #1459854

Change-Id: I0edb4fc7f2d6d4a3c23f395b4c2a611c0e954425

commit_message:
Fix issues with extra specs in VMAX driver

This patch is related to https://review.openstack.org/162658.
It continues to address the problem with the extra specs.
Extra specs should not be overwritten by the config file settings.

Change-Id: Ie30d0165b17ceb7c12aff6783232eb3b827df930
Closes-Bug: #1439506

commit_message:
Fix the wrong order of parameters when using assertEqual

The first parameter is the expected value while the second
parameter is the actual value.

Change-Id: I2584a3ee5f32e8e6fde00fef0d909b7389cfe262

commit_message:
Remove the deprecated ec2 token middleware

The ec2 token middleware has been deprecated in Juno, and has been moved to
keystonemiddleware repository. This change remove it from keystone in Liberty.

Partially implements: blueprint removed-as-of-liberty
Change-Id: I44a825e56d3cf5966acc546af3be2edd4cddc3e3

commit_message:
Remove un-used import at test_volume_transfer.py

There is an un-used import 'cinder.volume' at
ciner/tests/unit/api/contrib/test_volume_transfer.py.
Remove it, meanwhile there is using 'cinder.transfer.API'
at line #548 and line #581, so make the import consistent
by changed 'from cinder import transfer' to 'import cinder.transfer'.

Change-Id: I989c7b0a07e5e2836e41c0c922975f0c25b9ccdb
Closes-Bug: #1459497

commit_message:
Refactor Huawei Volume driver

This blueprint is an attempt to refactor the Huawei volume driver in liberty.
We will add a base dirver to implement the basic functions that the Cinder driver required.
The sub-class will inherit the base driver according to different storages.
the following diragram shows the structure of the newest Huawei volume driver

        +---------------+ +------------------+ +--------------------+
        | ISCSIDriver | | HuaweiBaseDriver | | FibreChannelDriver |
        +---------+-----+ +----+-------------+ +----+-----------+----+
                  | | | |
                  | | |__________ |
                  | | | |
              +---+--------------------+ +---+--------------------+
              | Huawei18000ISCSIDriver | | Huawei18000FCDriver |
              +-------------+----------+ +-------------+----------+

Change-Id: I202594f743423dcfe15e908057ae0cf6c22cc415
Implements: blueprint refactor-huawei-volume-driver

commit_message:
Add different version support for docker-py

As https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186610/
mentioned one point that distros packaging may have old
docker-py version, in order to have wide support about container
api, this change add more version support for execute deprecated
issue.

Closes-Bug: #1460976
Change-Id: I0d30afa95cb64a5761a829a47eb01af45fea42e7

Zhiyuan: As I suggested earlier, you should break the changes to vmware files out into a separate change, and then add it as a dependency for this change.

(My experience trying to do similar changes to this suggests that there are ~0 neutron cores who will approve changes to "other" parts of neutron - see Salvatore's comment above, for example - and you need to find at least 2x +2s ;)   The only way I found to make progress on cross-neutron changes is to split the change up into pieces that match the anticipated "core approval groups" within neutron - specifically break it out by vendor, and by advanced service (where that hasn't already been split into separate repos). commit_message:
Remove duplicate keys in dictionary

A code inspecting tool shows that there are duplicate keys in
some dictionary definitions. Remove them in this patch. Also
enable duplicate-key check in pylint.

Change-Id: I1aa221d2019853f905f2b8421dd45b0a3102baf0

commit_message:
Replace status code 403 with ForbiddenAction.code

It's not good to use magic number over the code, so replace them with
predefinition object.

Change-Id: I30e5f9709a2fef1c3e67fe0cdabd6963f5d84e20

commit_message:
Run WSGI with group=keystone

This matches puppet-keystone[*] and is required for distributions
which properly restricted access to /etc/keystone

[*] https://github.com/stackforge/puppet-keystone/blob/master/manifests/wsgi/apache.pp#L167

Closes-Bug: #1456441

Change-Id: I7a80bdf1c1efaedfeba7d2834a858e3617f6529e

commit_message:
Removes discover from test-reqs

The discover package is part of Python 2.7, so we don't need
to explicitely require it. It's by the way annoying for
distribution package maintainers, as the file has to be
patched.

Change-Id: I3509111c5a6657c9f09bd6e9cf6580ee47401286
Depends-On: If4bbac7b5d14107037591e8916170841e17d0ef1

commit_message:
Drop py2.6 support for keystone middleware

Since it is not supported to run very modern Keystonemiddleware
with much older services, py26 is no longer needed for Kyestonemiddleware.

This will allow us to cleanup the test-requires and other py26-specific
requirements from the project.

Depends-On: I316d3ec56ade662cb5deeca0d3d48230c878f35d

Change-Id: If4bbac7b5d14107037591e8916170841e17d0ef1

commit_message:
Rename driver to backend and fix the inaccurate docstring

- The name of the argument is `memcached_backend` instead of
`memcached_driver`.
- `pooled_memcached` is also a valid memcached driver.

Closes-Bug: #1442510
Change-Id: I1fee60cff0ec4b2129cae69b68de5dc30533ec48

commit_message:
Use SolidFire snapshots for Cinder snapshots

This patch just replaces the use of clones on the SolidFire
backend for SolidFire Snapshot objects.  This isn't necessarily
an issue, but it is important necessary to do things like
consistency group snaps.

Note, that we have to keep compatability for things like
create_from_snapshot where the system may have clones that
were used for snapshots prior to updating the driver.

While we're here, we also removed the logging calls in the test
which shouldn't really be there, as well as the overly chatty
debug messages like "entering/leaving".  More cleanup work
can be done to logs but should be in their own patch.

Change-Id: Ia67b2b9e3c0bf3b0b1f991e958f8eac13830f9cc

commit_message:
Refactor Ironic's versioned objects to oslo.versionedobjects

Ironic has versioned objects, which is helpful to deal with
versioning. Versioned-object allow Ironic to be operated safely during
upgrades. But it is based on Ironic's own versioned objects implementation.

An common oslo lib oslo.versionedobjects is already existed and ready:
https://github.com/openstack/oslo.versionedobjects
It is reaonable to move Ironic to use oslo.versionedobjects.

Change-Id: Ia6125333cc108886dec1a153def1b511a23dbf52

[{'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-06-02 22:30:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9659, 'date': '2015-06-02 22:40:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I'm seeing a ton of new variables that are now part of a new "default theme".  That's super cool!

Where were the old equivalents?  I suspect they should be removed. 

Or I'm totally wrong and don't understand what's happening here.

It's a 50/50 chance either way.'}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-06-02 22:46:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

There are no new variables actually.  This is the default bootstrap _variables file that we were just pulling in via /static/bootstrap/... at the top of the file.

The 'overrides' I changed in the variables themselves.  This file only differs from the Default Bootstrap theme for those 4 variables now.

Pulling this file into our repo as our default theme will also give us any insight into future problems if the Bootstrap variables change and might possibly cause cascading problems."}, {'account_id': 11098, 'date': '2015-06-02 22:47:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Nicely done!'}, {'account_id': 13805, 'date': '2015-06-02 22:50:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Is all variable theming related? I think some are regarding layout. -1 since it is a little bit more than a question. :)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-02 23:14:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

All of the variables, including the ones pertaining to layout, are all the same ones that were already getting import via the @import "/bootstrap/scss/bootstrap/variables";

All of these variables are themeing related, as they are the variables that are defined within a bootstrap theme.

None of the variables are new or changed.  They are simply now located within the theme folder instead of always pulling the variables from within /static/, which means that the configured theme would always be ignored.'}, {'account_id': 14064, 'date': '2015-06-02 23:44:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 13805, 'date': '2015-06-02 23:57:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks Diana for the detailed explanation. This is a great work! However I am not very comfortable with having all variables (theming + layout) defined in a file under /theme/.   Theming for me is about the below css properties:

color, background, border-color, shadows for box and text.

But scss variable can be about other things as well, like layout-related numbers, typography, animation etc. Even for Bootstrap, they have the similar concept. If I install bootstrap with Bower, I will get a bootstrap-theme.css and a bootstrap.css. In bootstrap-theme.css, it has and only has theme-related css rules defined there: color, background, border-color, shadows for box and text, while bootstrap.css includes everything else.

That said, this is matter of naming. If others find it is ok to put every variable in a file under /theme/, I would be happy with it as well. :-)'}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-06-03 00:44:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Actually, I think that a theme is about more than just color, padding, box-shadows, etc ... its about the entire look and feel of an application.

I think that a theme can definitely include many things beyond that, like layout-related numbers, typography and especially animation ... even responsive breakpoints.

Any part of the User Experience that I can customize with _variables.scss / _styles.scss can be part of a custom theme.'}, {'account_id': 13805, 'date': '2015-06-03 01:11:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks Diana. I would leave the -1 there for reminding core, not going to block the merge.

@core reviewers:
-1 shouldn't be considered a blocker is the matters mentioned there is not bothering you. I do not have strong opinion on it, but rather drawing your attention."}, {'account_id': 13785, 'date': '2015-06-03 16:31:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Looks good Diana.

@Sean, I think you're right that this might just be a naming issue. Things like typography and layout should be configurable along with colors and such. Maybe that 'themes' folder needs to be renamed to something more appropriate."}, {'account_id': 6650, 'date': '2015-06-03 21:20:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Shaoquan Chen - there is no need to leave a -1 around for questions / drawing attention.  Reviewers will read feedback.   If you really don't like it that is fine to leave -1 in there."}, {'account_id': 13805, 'date': '2015-06-03 21:36:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Eric Peterson, it is a -1, just wanted to say it is not a strong one. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 5623, 'date': '2015-06-04 00:07:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

theming certainly has a broader scope than colors and fonts, IMO. Themes are desired to differentiate, we providing a mechanism to do that without having to hack up the existing CSS. 

Additionally, we build upon bootstrap, these are the values bootstrap provides to toggle in theming/skinning. We don't need to restrict them."}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-06-04 00:53:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-04 00:54:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Bootstrap variables should derive from a known theme.

In openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard/scss/_variables.scss, the 4
bootstrap variables 'overrides' should actually come from the theme.
Instead of pulling in the very basic Bootstrap skin for overrides,
the default theme should bring in the default Bootstrap and change
the appropriate variables for horizon.

Change-Id: Ib017ca378b5cbc727f7e0f5055d98c41f159435e
Closes-Bug: #1457188

Besides removing the teannt_id parameter from create_port, I decided to refractor create_port and update_port methods.

First off, create_port doesn't need to distinguish between omitted and None-valued args. None parameters are just not passed to neutron port_create.

Secondly, I defined _ns_() which is the default value for all optional parameters of update_port. If user want to deassign a value, they can just use None explicitly.

This change seems more clear and explicit to me wrt validate_arguments used in a earlier patch."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-12 11:26:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
Split security group list operations

Security groups can come from either nova or neutron or not be
available by the vendor. This uses a new flag from os-client-config
to determine where we should get the list from. Also, a new exception
is added for features that are not supported.

This required a minimum version bump in os-client-config.

Change-Id: I4474341ebc255700a06247846c6350981437e8ae

commit_message:
Add keystone endpoint resource methods

This change adds keystone endpoint resource methods to
OperatorClouds instances.

Only Keystone v2 API is currently supported.

Change-Id: Idf3bd7500f5853ec329945d8c8203bd7b6aed52f

commit_message:
adjust alarm post ut code to adapt to upstream wsme

wsme has upgraded from 0.6.4 to 0.7.0, and now it supports convert
int and str to boolean, which causes our unit test code failed.

This change adjust the affected unit test code to adapt to such
changes.

Change-Id: Ic0d098e8e689e2421f261a72744abc3da576d8b2
Closes-Bug: #1460869
(cherry picked from commit a5b04650c8735551320176c5822d021d562412b5)

commit_message:
Revised heat driver and profile

This patch removes the local 'hack' or heat stack resource. This is
possible because SDK now contains a working version of stack resource.
This patch also makes heat driver to call function apis instead of the
resource apis exposed by OpenStack SDK.

Change-Id: Ifbb3f0468bcefb0afc3c245ec1e0fa5d7a2da254

commit_message:
Revert "Ensure DIB_RELEASE is exported for fedora"

The default release for fedora is actually 21 for us, and we are unable
to build 22 right now.

This reverts commit 379d6a26503b5b1830b4994cfbef1560e14617a1.

Change-Id: Iffcc505f1e115cb6bc662b57a78878e498ce338e

commit_message:
I/O error uploading image

Fixed two errors when upload an image from a file.
One is the file name doesn't exist error.
Another is file got closed in a new thread since Django 1.7.

Change-Id: Ia64c385d89e0d938b14182f2744251f76b892eac
Closes-Bug: #1451429
(cherry picked from commit 810ad30607fff86fdb8c9b78fe0ac32d09259b78)

commit_message:
Update hacking and fix hacking violations

This does a few things:

* Update hacking to the version in global-requirements. Old hacking was
  installing a version of pbr that was breaking other packages.

* Fix all the hacking/pep8 rules that updating hacking raised.

* Do some general docstring cleanup, while already in there cleaning up
  a bunch of docstrings due to H405 violations.

Change-Id: I1fc1e59d4c3d7b14631f8b576e3f3854bc452188
Closes-Bug: #1461717

commit_message:
Revert "Remove Brick from cinder codebase"

This reverts commit 88da45569cdfb900ec54d5ec73fecef0d75eef4e.

Turns out that os-brick wasn't actually ready and isn't able to accept commits/updates.  Suggest we revert back to being able to maintain our code while folks figure out how to get the library up and working and what the rules are going to be for commits.

https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+os-brick,n,z

Change-Id: I1c8a7a61727e893861b06632670d45426eba9828

commit_message:
Rely on defaults being present

There will always be a fleshed out defaults dict now, so don't spend a
lot of effort in dealing with one not being there.

Change-Id: I93cea42c6e35457de1f2d8d1e37ead2ff41fba3a

commit_message:
Consume os_client_config defaults as base defaults

In 99% of invocations, os_client_config will be passing in default
values. However, if someone decides to just construct an OpenStackCloud
without going through os_client_config, there will be defaults missing.
Grab the defaults from os_client_config and use them, even if they
aren't passed in as arguments.

Change-Id: I25a1ff3eeba445f91b9bde8cd4e2d68b72b06136

Add support for asymmetric and certificate orders, as well as various
attributes useful to interact with them.

commit_message:
Remove Brick from cinder codebase

This patch removes the existing brick initiator code from Cinder.
The new os-brick pypi library takes over.

The only thing left behind is the local_dev directory
as it's not part of os-brick.   We should possibly
move this elsewhere in a follow up patch.

Change-Id: Iaa22b30b852ea055a8698e0faaefa5caff84d090
Depends-On: I0096e76f958e04829b98d5c4c47f49c82b58d8aa

commit_message:
Fix cinder scenario: create nested snapshots

Volume size cannot be smaller than the snapshot size. They
must be >= original snapshot size. This change fix this
possible size mismatching, occurs due creating resouces with
random size.

Change-Id: Ib95ff354a2d2f0b59ff982365729d306618294c9
Closes-Bug: #1457866

commit_message:
Added postinstall hook to trigger tox

This adds a postinstall script invocation to invoke tox, so that
non-npm and non-bower dependencies are resolved before we run
our tests.

Change-Id: I4e573679f46e539c3949a3c839d246b5bed78e45

commit_message:
Replace blacklist_functions with blacklist_calls

The bandit security scan is currently skipping any check of
blacklisted functions. The bandit plugin should be blacklist_calls
and not blacklist_functions.

Change-Id: I167220f5f8edcc450b5891f6396e164500504df5
Closes-Bug: #1460839

commit_message:
Update access control configuration in httpd config

Not every distribution uses SELinux (some use AppArmor for
example). It's confusing to tell those deployers to use SELinux.

Co-Authored-By: Lin Hua Cheng
Change-Id: I4e80f47aada52fd555f30c55ae1996c56c2db59c

cleans them up.

commit_message:
Don't rely on token_info for header building

We already have an auth_ref object that will abstract the differences
between v2 and v3 tokens. Use that instead of inspecting the token data
directly.

Change-Id: I811cecbcd8eeac4638ce4e4ec312a8504678984b

commit_message:
Remove hacking select line

Contrary to popular belief, this does not mean "also check this".
It means "only check this and don't check anything else".  So this
was testing _only_ H321.

Change-Id: I8ae173e62d57232cec1bf751004fe4213214353b

commit_message:
Use EntityNotFound instead of VolumeSnapshotNotFound/VolumeTypeNotFound

This patch will use EntityNotFound instead of
VolumeSnapshotNotFound and VolumeTypeNotFound.
And will remove the two old exception class definition.

Change-Id: I661c7b6b306da34f30c55914f74eebc6e8e16931
Closes-Bug: #1461343

commit_message:
Move _check_active to nova client plugin

The method was practically identical in Instance and Server resources,
with only difference in reported resource type as part of error message.

Some mocks that mocked this method directly on resource object were
modified accordingly in unit tests.

The new `_check_active` is made to accept both Nova server objects and server
UUIDs/strings. This will allow changing methods of server resources
(and tests!) one-by-one.

Added a new method `fetch_server` that tolerates intermittent failures
when fetching a fresh server object (similar to existing `refresh_server`).

Unit tests for `_check_active` and `fetch_server` added.

Related-Bug: #1393268
Change-Id: I1b63dbd9182cc8519f43ff859a408d49789263dd

commit_message:
Move project included validation

It's invalid to have a v2 token where there isn't a project attached.
This is a validation step and doesn't belong in the header building
function.

Change-Id: Ib17b18f597e55000168335b0874e4e85dfa0feca

commit_message:
Add pip to requirements list

A possible solution to the bug reported by Peter Martini where
other dependencies are causing pip to become broken.  In this case
we attempt to upgrade pip via the requirements file.

Change-Id: I4b1f4c4241e20e061f15c7834199cb1a6cf5111c
Closes-Bug: #1459947

commit_message:
Drop nova_meta and glance_registry on public vip

This patch removes the public VIP for the nova metadata
and glance registry services.

Change-Id: I0878f7b3eeed6e16c5d30bdf76ebca56eb49d042

This looks good, my only question is if there is a more generic way we can solve this - it seems like we're moving to a hook per deployment tool (atomic, docker-compose etc), but in theory those tools could all be run via a generic software config resource, right?

e.g:

https://github.com/hardys/heat-templates/blob/docker-host/hot/software-config/example-templates/example-docker-script.yaml#L67

I think this approach is perfectly fine, and it's a bit tidier, but I wonder if we should also have some generic examples, particularly given the current proliferation of different ways to launch a container - we should make it easy for folks to use whatever tool they want (and the generic approach makes it slightly easier vs writing a new hook per tool).

Just a thought, I'm not blocking on it :)"}, {'account_id': 866, 'date': '2015-04-01 16:29:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2015-04-07 08:20:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

This hook looks good, but I share the same opinion that Steven expressed: we are starting to have quite a number of hooks now, and I wonder whether we will have to have a new hooks every two weeks or so when a new Docker deployment tools pops up. Would really be nice to have some generic approach (might be just documentation and examples) to solve this without having to write a new hook.'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2015-04-07 08:56:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I agree with Steve that we need more examples to use generic script hook for these use cases.

Atomic tool is very specific to RHEL/Fedora Atomic Host(at least as of now), initially written only to deploy super privileged containers. 

I wrote this hook for the Tripleo team, who plan to use atomic tool to deploy OpenStack control plane services on atomic host. 

IMO, having hooks for the commonly used tools for container deployment would definitely be useful for the users. However, we probably can't maintain 100s of them.

As per my understanding the future direction from docker ecosystem  is around docker-compose and k8s. Therefore we would maintain these 3 hooks."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2015-04-07 21:16:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Wouldn't this require a custom built atomic image with the whole heat-config-agent stack running in atomic? I thought the whole point of atomic was that the host OS is never customised?

I was assuming that this would be for boot config only, so you could specify what container(s) to run on boot, and one of those containers could contain the heat-config-agent to manage the deployment resources from there on."}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2015-04-08 02:32:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

We don't need custom built atomic image. This hook would be part of the heat-docker-agent container, that would be deployed during boot.

This is being used here. Probably would be more clear.

https://github.com/rthallisey/atomic-osp-installer/blob/master/heat/example-pristine-atomic-openstack.yaml

Atomic tool is a python tool/script that can be used with any OS(depends on docker and docker-py). Therefore once it's packaged it can be used with other OS and we can have custom images with disk-image-builder

Reg this being used for boot-config, we can use it in place of direct 'docker run' command for the heat-docker-agent service. 

As docker takes some time to start after boot, we probably to keep heat-docker-agent as a systemd service rather than make only an atomic install/run."}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2015-04-15 09:55:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi All,

I've included this hook directly in container-boot-config 
patch[1], as there is no option atm to build a custom image with 'atomic tool'(no fedora or pypi package yet), so the dib elements are not required. We can add them back when the packages are available.

This hook can only be be used with the 'heat-container-agent' on pristine fedora-atomic or rhel-atomic 7.1.

 
[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/164572/"}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2015-04-15 09:55:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2015-04-24 10:24:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-24 10:45:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add tests and example template for atomic hook

Atomic hook can be used with bootconfig to deply containers using
atomic tool in rhel 7.1. This patch adds test and exmaple template
for the hook.

Change-Id: I0f2469225027f3d37c7dd59f85dee8b5aa24a874

commit_message:
Add sub-project lieutenants

A recent patch added the concept of Lieutenants for Neutron.  This
same concept makes a lot of sense for identifying clear points of
contact for the various sub-projects under the Neutron tent.  This
patch adds a table of the projects currently approved as part of
Neutron in the governance repo.  I also made a guess on who the
lieutenant would be based on reviews in stackalytics (except for ones
that weren't in stackalytics).

Change-Id: Ibce5d6ba5e19dec59a10c88749557509136c4e41
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Refactor type_tunnel/gre/vxlan to reduce duplicate code

gre and vxlan type drivers have similar implementations for multiple
methods:
* get_endpoint_by_host
* get_endpoint_by_ip
* delete_endpoint
* get_endpoints
* add_endpoint

This change abstracts these methods and moves the abstractions to the
new class EndpointTunnelTypeDriver.

Change-Id: Iab97f8283b6bf5586334958de950664f6e74202a

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 14817, 'date': '2015-06-03 15:27:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Inherit files when restore

We use stack.prepare_abandon() to make the
snapshot data, but the data have no 'files' then will
result in ValueError raised(No content found in the "files"
section for get_file path) when restore.
This patch will store 'files' for snapshot data(
also for prepare abandon data), then we can get 'files'
from the snapshot data when stack restore.

Change-Id: I0fddf92e950b93dce70eb8e5a562cf8d0046a9ab
Closes-Bug: #1461375

commit_message:
Consolidate test-requirements files.

The bandit and functional files don't add much and aren't updated by
update.py, nor are they standard where we'd want to teach update.py
about them.

Some functional tests take a long time, but are vital. This will allow
for those tests to claim responsibility for setting their own reasonable
timeout.

commit_message:
Update keystoneclient requirement

Update keystoneclient to the latest release. This brings a bunch of
features that services can rely on, however is particularly needed for
OpenStackClient to bring up V3 API coverage for moving devstack to
keystone V3 only.

Steps to reproduce it:
1. Select an existing subnet.
2. In the subnet detail, change the allocation pools value.
3. Click Save.
4. Click the changed subnet detail and check the allocation pool value.

Root cause: The problem is that we only allow a new subnet to set the allocation pool.
Seems like we can do that via api during update and so we should enable that on Horizon.

'}]
commit_message:
User should be able to update allocation pool values.

Steps to reproduce it:
1. Select an existing subnet.
2. In the subnet detail, change the allocation pools value.
3. Click Save.
4. Click the changed subnet detail and check the allocation pool value.

Root cause: The problem is that we only allow a new subnet to set the allocation pool.
Seems like we can do that via api during update and so we should enable that on Horizon.

Change-Id: I9e6b0ee427ca9af82c4ed80abc1e7c19fe81641f
Closes-bug: 1458803
Closes-bug: 1458769
(cherry picked from commit 3b6dacca71e0cfb69786a7b5713a151f59d2682d)

Remove deprecation check in tests

commit_message:
Rework of check functions in muranomanager.py

- Check ports function reworked to give possibility check
multi-instance murano environment deployment
- Using python-muranoclient for significant part of functions
- Added one more step to Wordpress murano test to check ports availability
- Up RAM requirements from 2048 to 4096 for Murano suite because of
Wordpress test spawns 2 VM

Change-Id: Ie39070bac20efe9a2b7b306e426702941be3a3a4
Closes-Bug: #1461104

commit_message:
Add domain support for ec2creds in v3 identity

A follow up work item from I52ff2020ef2fcbdc8a98280b73c6fd4a93bc8e0f
to support domain scoped users and projects for ec2creds in the
v3 identity api.

Related-Bug: 1236326

Change-Id: If4ac5356ade8cff347bb9eb9f88d1ace82bb7275

commit_message:
Added CORS support middleware to Ironic

This adds the CORS support middleware to Ironic, allowing a deployer
to optionally configure rules under which a javascript client may
break the single-origin policy and access the API directly.

OpenStack Spec:
   https://review.openstack.org/#/c/179866/
Oslo_Middleware Docs:
   http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html
Global Requirements Patch (merged):
   https://review.openstack.org/#/c/179926/

Change-Id: I7f5f016b486154bcd138321ce3cd58782f76c657

commit_message:
Print help on help command

Change it so that 'cliffdemo help' prints the full help, not the
help for the help command.  'cliffdemo help help' can be used to
print the help for the help command.  Running 'cliffdemo help'
will be similar to running 'cliffdemo --help'.

Change-Id: I1b3e5448b2cf357ae65ca86e1131165aff023c39

commit_message:
Provide a helper method to get requests ssl values

There is a weird logic around the interaction between how the openstack
things all accept cacert and verify/insecure parameters and how requests
wants them. Rather than spreading the parameter combining logic across
the universe, put it here.

Note that this inverts the usual requests logic in that !verify will
override the presence of a cacert value and cause verification to NOT
occur.  This is intended to become the normal mode of operation for
OpenStack clients.

Change-Id: I3c76d9a10e6e5d60a593ceefc87dafdc6857d9c6

commit_message:
Consolidating redundant code in the tests

This moves things that are pretty much copy-paste into one place,
letting us focus on the actual differences amongst the tests.

I've also made the local test fixtures explicit, so we can see what
each test really needs, which has also eliminated redundant test
overhead, the slowest test is now 0.05s vs 0.1 before. This is more
than paid for by the reduced duplication in the basic setup, making
the patch a net reduction in LOC.

It also fixes the tempdir leak that was present in two of the test
scripts.

Change-Id: I63eee7681657b2b5eb7959738cc89c57c117fa3b

commit_message:
Guru Meditation Reports broken without version_string

The versions from many openstack projects don't provide the
vendor_string,product_string,version_string_with_package.
We need to keep compatible with these projects.

Change-Id: I688ef29b84541d3261f6b9395b3f591b276aa071
Closes-Bug:#1456465

the global requirements

commit_message:
Add EC2 support for identity v3 API

EC2 support is provided for the v2 identity API and is available in
almost exactly the same format in the v3 API and enabled by default.

Supporting EC2 in the v3 identity API in OSC will make it much easier to
transition devstack to a v3 only state.

Closes-Bug: 1236326

Change-Id: I52ff2020ef2fcbdc8a98280b73c6fd4a93bc8e0f

commit_message:
Huawei manila driver code refactoring

The Huawei manila driver code should be restructured.
Instead of using a loose interface definition of share
drivers, use the ABC python library to build abstract
classes that enforces the driver to implement the needed
functionality.

The huawei_helper.py is too long, the code structure
should be adjusted.

Change-Id: I4fa6434b397becccab75ceb1f181394a278b249a
Partially-Implements: blueprint huawei-manila-driver-refactor

This is intentional, the ^H is a common idiom, it's the backspace character. Please leave as is.

An educated user knows that "change from the crypt^h^h^h^h cloud" means "change from the cloud".

But yes, this is not common knowledge nowadays. For the target group - operators - we can assume that they know.'}, {'account_id': 9382, 'date': '2015-06-03 18:06:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Remove deprecated neutron_* configuration settings

neutron_* configuration settings have been deprecated since Juno release,
new items in [neutron] section should be referenced in doc.

indexer: enable MySQL schema migration test

commit_message:
Enable random hash seeds

neutron-vpnaas tests have been updated in order to support random hash
seed. It allows to remove PYTHONHASHSEED=0 in tox.ini and remove
hashtest tox environment.

Change-Id: I94c160c56d074c7a14aaae1fff379fc1c51bd16a
Partial-Bug: #1348818

commit_message:
Change ComputeHost table to filter on host field

ComputeHost table was trying to filter on a field that didn't exist
leading to a template rendering error when the filter was applied, so
this patch changes from 'service.type' to 'service.host' as the filtered
field.

Change-Id: I66a47a98f4005689b7be73bec46fa3ea4b9472af
Closes-Bug: 1390089
(cherry picked from commit dd487f236db15fe6d6de76eb86fe98b75e2987b6)

[{'created': '2014-11-10 18:12:43.000000000', 'message': 'Honor keystone policy file when creating client

When creating the keystone client for an admin the user is checked
for the specific role of "admin" to determine if they are authorized
to use the admin URL. This patch changes this logic so that the
policy file is honored instead of a specific role.

Closes-Bug: #1336418
Change-Id: I600334dff17a5564f97cbcce67ff6d3619142961
(cherry picked from commit 45ae78ce85c8ecc211c7c957c6409955588f831a)
'}]
commit_message:
Honor keystone policy file when creating client

When creating the keystone client for an admin the user is checked
for the specific role of "admin" to determine if they are authorized
to use the admin URL. This patch changes this logic so that the
policy file is honored instead of a specific role.

Closes-Bug: #1336418
Change-Id: I600334dff17a5564f97cbcce67ff6d3619142961
(cherry picked from commit 45ae78ce85c8ecc211c7c957c6409955588f831a)

commit_message:
Make datepicker display in front of modals

This patch changes the styling of the datepicker so that it will
always display in front of a modal. This is needed when a field
that is displayed on a modal uses the datepicker widget. Without
this fix the datepicker displays behind the modal.

Closes-Bug: #1364649
Change-Id: I79f97fccceb29d438520845107e239ec5b66c025

commit_message:
Catch missing 404 exceptions in client

Whenever an entity wasn't found, the ceilometerclient would issue a
NotFound exception. Which is fine, except that it's not the exception
that was being expected in the client at all. This exception was defined
in the apiclient in the openstack/common directory. So, instead this
exception is now being caught in the manager, and now the appropriate
exception is being raised.

There were some functions where, if the entity was not to be found, a
404 exception would be raised, which was never caught by the client
since it was expecting the function to return None, instead of raising.
This CR fixes that.

Closes-Bug: #1451833
Change-Id: I47b34af2df9c85f86ba1f7f4d7b2951f8d27f96c

commit_message:
Fedora 22 is not ready for DIB

There are too many vast differences in fc22 to simply change the
DIB_RELEASE to 22 today. We will need to decide if we're to
install the now deprecated yum, or revamp all of our yum related
code to also work with dnf.

Partially-Closes-Bug: 1461631
Change-Id: I73656e5e302ce7c4ce353640784a2c4dd69a95da

commit_message:
Create yum vars directory

Not all rpm bases distros have this directory. Fails on Fedora.
Simple check, if the directory doesn't exist, make it.

Change-Id: I71e3e236f6cc41061586d39ff8230c3fa4108936
Closes-Bug: 1461615

commit_message:
Various devstack cleanups

* Do not create the public network if its been created already

* Explicitly disable neutron services that do not need to run (they are
enabled by default in the gate)

* Remove subnets twice: There is some issue with the masking of port subne IDs
we do that is causing issue when removing subnets in devstack. It works the second
time?

* Stop using a hard-coded network name

* Stop q-svc using the correct function depending on screen config: stop_process
pkills the thing and leaves a q-svc.failure flag file when using screen, that
fails the devstack run.

Change-Id: I5d088e2cb485a6ae74d45d738a0083cba4b66ff8

commit_message:
Make blessed an optional dependency

blessed is not in openstack g-r and blocks us from aligning there. This makes
the dependency optional.  If it is not installed, the cli browse command emits
a warning telling the user to install it.  The browse section of the CLI is the
only place its used and doesn't affect any other functionality.

Change-Id: If446c2135936c8ea4083eb9fc712a98031b28ac4

commit_message:
Make MockFixedIntervalLoopingCall class as a helper class

MockFixedIntervalLoopingCall class is used in both the classes
TestOvsNeutronAgent and TestOvsDvrNeutronAgent.

This patch removes the MockFixedIntervalLoopingCall from both the
places and make it as a helper class in test_ovs_neutron_agent.py.
So that it will be used everywhere in test_ovs_neutron_agent.py.

Change-Id: I5e0803436e91b4f20ec03209e9e799a68df4eaf4

commit_message:
Switch from deprecated isotime

oslo_utils.timeutils.isotime() is deprecated as of 1.6 so we need
to stop using it.

The deprecation message says to use datetime.datetime.isoformat()
instead, but the format of the string generated by isoformat isn't
the same as the format of the string generated by isotime. The string
is used in tokens and other public APIs and we can't change it
without potentially breaking clients.

So the workaround is to copy the current implementation from
oslo_utils.timeutils.isotime() to keystone.common.utils.isotime().

Closes-Bug: 1461251

Change-Id: Icf821be8cd4ee7f52c1a3d89bfed302488c080f2

commit_message:
Deleting ports before deletion of routers in resource_cleanup

In resource_cleanup need to delete ports before deleting the
routers. This is required in a private nuage thirdparty
testcase because a router-interface-delete is not allowed
when a port is present under that router. Also a port
resource sits beneath a router resource, and this change
would not affect any other tempest testcase.

Change-Id: I82a2cc9338a037f3b0d087c8f7c50c9cd0d0627b
Closes-Bug:1460223

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Just a nit: in the commit message.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-04-29 21:08:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

We still need to add logic to cleanup the leftover iptables rules and move the port to the dead VLAN. I confirmed that it leaves rules with this patch by doing the following:

* boot a nova VM
* get the VM's port ID
* run 'sudo iptables-save | grep <first-five-chars-of-port-ID>' to see the iptables rules
* terminate the instance
* run iptables-save again and still see the rules from the port


The agent may automatically move it to the dead VLAN but we need to verify to make sure a tenant can't delete his/her port from the neutron API manually and still have a VM attached to the network without any iptables filtering rules."}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2015-04-30 01:01:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

kevin, I did the same for many times and no rules are left after deleting the VM. I must have missed something.'}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2015-04-30 01:07:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hmm, I just realized that it's 'neutron port-delete <port-id>' that is associated with a VM, rather than 'nova delete <vm>'."}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2015-04-30 22:30:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-30 22:58:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add VIF_DELETED notification event to Nova

It's possible to delete a neutron port that is currently associated
with an instance. When it happens, neutron should notify nova of the
port deletion event so that Nova can take proper actions.

Refer to I998b6bb80cc0a81d665b61b8c4a424d7219c666f for the nova patch
that handles the event.

Change-Id: Iff88cd12ae18017ef3e776821bcf3ecf3b4f052f
Related-Bug: #1333365
Related-Bug: #1448148

Setting timeout to a default of False in get_auth()

commit_message:
Make default get_auth timeout be None

Setting timeout to a default of False in get_auth()
results in a requests timeout of 0.0 in keystoneclient,
which causes a connection failure.

This bug will cause func tests to not run when using
keystoneauth.

Added unit tests to verify correct default timeout is set
in get_auth().

Drive-by: remove what seems like a stale TODO comment

Change-Id: I17c781ce160a682b1768d315422ade0cdd2df198

commit_message:
Allow querying for migrations by source_compute only

The existing filtering only allows source-or-dest querying, and for
evacuate we want to look for things only *from* our host.

Related to blueprint robustify-evacuate

Change-Id: I05dbc71e969bcb8f64e6aa3b979cc0ffc75c1205

commit_message:
Download debian netboot installer each time

Currently if debian netboot installer is already downloaded we skip
downloading and start provisioning. It's an error-prone approach
because the installer may stuck if its kernel version mismatch
archive's kernel version. This patch starts to download debian
installer each time we start provisioning.

Closes-Bug: #1461206

Change-Id: Ia6b8653461e604ae05f306406e8a3515a593fc53

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: I6486d3afc5d47385d8c920018d5652b555407002

commit_message:
Add list of image params needed to disable agents

Some clouds have an in-instance agent to handle things like online
password resets and other such activities. When building and uploading
images, it's often advantageous to not install such an agent and instead
handle such things via config management... but doing so requires data
to be set on the image itself.

Change-Id: I5b7c9d72fd2d49890bc466d7dd22a3cb9595f670

subject: Add Python 3.4 compatibility to bandit
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 6486, 'name': 'Brant Knudson', 'email': 'blk@acm.org', 'username': 'blk-u'}, {'_account_id': 8119, 'name': 'Eric Brown', 'email': 'browne@vmware.com', 'username': 'ericwb'}, {'_account_id': 11029, 'name': 'Jamie Finnigan', 'email': 'jamiefinnigan@gmail.com', 'username': 'jamiefinnigan'}, {'_account_id': 11716, 'name': 'Tim Kelsey', 'email': 'timothy.kelsey@uk.ibm.com', 'username': 'tkelsey'}, {'_account_id': 11861, 'name': 'Travis McPeak', 'email': 'tmcpeak@us.ibm.com', 'username': 'travis-mcpeak'}, {'_account_id': 12000, 'name': 'Ian Cordasco', 'email': 'sigmavirus24@gmail.com', 'username': 'sigmavirus24'}, {'_account_id': 15173, 'name': 'Rob Fletcher', 'email': 'rfletch.vol@gmail.com', 'username': 'fletcher'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-05-27 23:00:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-05-27 23:01:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-27 23:08:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-bandit-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/12/186212/1/check/gate-bandit-pep8/ac3b543/ : SUCCESS in 34s
- gate-bandit-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/12/186212/1/check/gate-bandit-python27/5bc655e/ : SUCCESS in 31s'}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-05-28 00:45:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This is going to be awesome Ian.  Just to be clear, is this to support scanning Python 3 code (does this already work?), to support running Bandit in Python 3.x interpreter, or both?

Sorry, I'm a Py3 noob ;)

One definite advantage of having support for running on Python 3.x is that we can create a universal wheel for distribution."}, {'account_id': 15173, 'date': '2015-05-28 02:22:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This isn't exactly related, but I would *love* to be able to write rules against specific versions of Python.

e.g. "Python 2.3, httplib sucks" -> "Python 3.0, httplib sucks less"

Maybe that's a thing already and I'm not aware?'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-05-28 08:34:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Ian, thanks for taking this on, its been on my personal roadmap for bandit but I have had no bandwidth to start.

@Travis, this will be for running bandit on Py3, scanning should work already.

@Rob, interesting idea, though I don't know how python interpreter/lib versions become relevant to static code analysis. We cant say what version the scanned code will be run under, only what version Bandit is running on when it scans the code. commit_message:
Add Python 3.4 compatibility to bandit

This includes a number of changes to make this happen:

- We handle the fact that in Python 3.3 and later, ast.TryExcept and
  ast.TryFinally were replaced by ast.Try

- We handle the fact that ast.NameConstant is now the node type for
  True/False

- We handle the cases where map and range need to return lists

- We remove a property from the result store to prevent errors assigning
  to the underlying attribute

- We check for exec conditionally based on the version of Python

- We use proper octal notation, e.g., 0o755

Change-Id: I71c0bb61c9ee0bf1b751a719a4eb95bf7a0b4943

Update the directory path of LBaaS/FWaaS in cloud admin guide

The directory paths of LBaaS/FWaaS remain of the old path.
Other paths of LBaaS/FWaaS is confirmed in all of manuals by manually.

commit_message:
Stop hard coding core team member lists

All of the project json files had lists of the core review team
members.  Since this was originally written, gerrit has added a REST
API and this information is available through that API.  Get the info
from there instead when we can.

There are a few project files I didn't convert because the equivalent
gerrit team wasn't immediately obvious.

Change-Id: Ie7ae19d9a58a5148002676604fd6962ea1438786
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Dell SC: update_volume_stats could use uninitialized vars

In _update_volume_stats in dell_storagecenter_common.py totalcapacitygb
and freespacegb are not necessarily initialized in the LOG.debug call.
Changed to data['total_capacity_gb'] and data['free_capacity_gb'].

Also initialized to total_capacity_gb and free_capacity_gb dict entries
to 'unavailable' which allowed the removal of two conditionals in the
same function.

Change-Id: Ib699e0d1cf67645298628aa96656888193843509
Closes-Bug: #1461230

commit_message:
Fix the devstack settings admin account handling

The current settings file has a hard coded admin username
and password.  This change pulls the admin password and username
in from the devstack environment.

Change-Id: If2bbd62fa4c92ac1b26d0aaf74e0cd26c553fa75

TL;DR: I'd like to enable developers to put more effort in descriptive config options help texts.

A short background what I try to achieve. I started working on OpenStack 1 year ago and noticed that the configuration options are exhaustive. It was (and still is) cumbersome for me to figure out which service relies on which options, and which options interact with each other. During the development of patch [1] I noticed that I don't have a means to see how the configuration reference guide would look like with the enhanced help text of my patch. Right now there are no formatting options for config options help text so it doesn't seem to be important to have a "visual check", but I hope that this changes over the time.

It's very possible that I'm on the wrong track with this change here. I'll put more thoughts into it.

commit_message:
let the autohelp_wrapper use local repos

The autohelp_wrapper uses as git URL for the projects the URL
git://git.openstack.org/openstack. This is not configurable.
Because of that, the build of guides (e.g. the configuration
reference) based on local (not yet commited) branches was not
possible.
This change set offers a new parameter for the script to use
another URL for the projects (e.g. to a local one).

Example:
The command to build the config options table of a local nova branch
(with the name "docs_serial_console") which is in the local folder
"~/git" would look like this:
    ./autohelp-wrapper -g ~/git -b docs_serial_console docbook nova

Change-Id: I03e5491221ac03be596b243183bdeb98c63dd03e

commit_message:
Add Endpoint Enforcement to Keystonemiddleware

Adds configurable options to enable endpoint enforcement
in Keystonemiddleware within auth_token middleware.

Co-Authored-By: David Charles Kennedy <david.c.kennedy@hp.com>
Implements: endpoint-enforcement-middleware
Change-Id: Iad486f28455b63a5ce216595b9c184cf33d104ea

commit_message:
Move full-stack logs post-tests

Currently, it's up to the developer who wants to run full-stack on his
machine to make the directory in question (/opt/stack/logs). However,
this also means that the files don't get compressed at the end of a gate
run. Now, each full-stack test will have each own log directory in /tmp.
Once the logs are there, post_test_hook.sh can run 'gzip' on all the log
files before moving them to /opt/stack/logs on its own.

Change-Id: I5c04d0af0b9858722ae0c4baf0ee478ffb078e02

commit_message:
Deal with PEP-0476 certificate chaining checking

PEP-0476 introduced more thorough certificate chain verification
for HTTPS connectivity; this was introduced in Python 2.7.9, and
breaks a number of unit tests in the keystone codebase.

Disable certificate chain verification for keystone SSL tests
using the backwards compatible SSLContext provided for this
purpose.

Conflicts:
	keystone/tests/test_ssl.py

Change-Id: I6b5e975ed4c9abf3571212ba0e172eb653bb9281
Closes-Bug: #1403068
(cherry picked from commit 89aec92962a551dc06520e284dadc63a0a58ad2c)

commit_message:
Add default domain to fixture.v3.V3FederationToken

Each ephemeral user is by default a member of service domain called
"Federated". We should reflect this in fixture.v3.V3FederationToken as
well.

Change-Id: I46a68048c4520e8bace4800b7635df3f8d351dd0

commit_message:
configure and start rabbitmq VMs from userdata

Configuring and starting rabbitmq with os-apply-config and
os-refresh-config seems to be causing issues where rabbitmq is being
regularly reset and restarted.  We want rabbitmq to be reset and started
once at initial boot and not past that.  Moving the config generation
and service startup logic to the userdata script that is supplied by Cue
at VM creation time.

Closes-Bug: 1453351

Change-Id: I2971c196e0cc106d17e18f868c491b589ecb17b8

commit_message:
Make InstanceExternalEvent use an Enum for status

We enforce status at the API layer, so we can convert this to an Enum for
better type correctness without doing any special acrobatics.

Change-Id: I9a22e53ca872235e723798d8ce3cb146d88568ab

commit_message:
Update example files to work on Python 2 & 3

Almost all of the problems were using print statements instead of
equivalent Python 3 syntax. You'll notice that in Python 2, the AST
parses `print(...)` and `print ...` equivalently:

    $ python
    Python 2.7.9 (default, Dec 15 2014, 10:01:34)
    [GCC 4.2.1 Compatible Apple LLVM 6.0 (clang-600.0.56)] on darwin
    Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
    >>> import ast
    >>> body = ast.parse('print("Foo")').body[0]
    >>> body
    <_ast.Print object at 0x1033452d0>
    >>> body.values
    [<_ast.Str object at 0x103345310>]
    >>> body2 = ast.parse('print "Foo"').body[0]
    >>> body2
    <_ast.Print object at 0x103345350>
    >>> body2.values
    [<_ast.Str object at 0x103345390>]

This leaves 2 files - exec.py, os-chmod.py - which are skipped due to
syntax errors on Python 3.4.

Change-Id: I2d97a249503317092372a874c018561cf875b066

commit_message:
Removed per ACL operations and added support for PUT method.

Changes has been done as per comments in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/178479/

All of APIs for /secrets/{uuid}/acls/{uuid} resource are removed.
ACL resource is changed to /secrets/{uuid}/acl.
PUT (complete update) support is added for above ACL resource.
PUT is used instead of POST for creating ACL resource as per API-WG recommendation.
GET on ACL resource will return response similar to request format.
PUT/PATCH will return above ACL resource reference in response.

Now as every secret or container has a default acl which is returned
on GET call when no explicit ACL is set. That's why PATCH will not
return 404 when used on secret/container with no explicit ACL.
Similarly DELETE will not return 404 on its invocation even if
explicit ACL is not set or called multiple times.

All of above changes are made to container ACL resource as well.

Change-Id: I5bfccf4cb827845084fd2d5d734f476f2ed16146

commit_message:
Don't pass read only attributes on neutron update

When making calls to neutron to update an IPv6 network
Horizon is passing read only attributes which fails,
making v6 subnets uneditable.

Correct the view logic to not include read only attrbutes
on an update.

Change-Id: I219337b54c1fc55c8012ba63dd57fc1bb00bc922
Closes-Bug: 1459446
(cherry picked from commit 55802f7b21a62fea56f994650e1d52915b6547fe)

add ips to novaclient server manager

This exposes the ips Resource from the nova server manager which the
infra team believes will help them optimize some of their API load on
various clouds.

commit_message:
Add an extension section to the developer docs.

This extension section provides guidance for deployers wanting to add
their own services and configuration to os-ansible-deployment.

This documentation also includes some recommendations for how projects
sourcing os-ansible-deployment might be structured.

Change-Id: I7ddac9ff2cab8b5a7cb9af1ba6bb3bdde64d60ea
Implements: blueprint developer-docs

commit_message:
Bump oslo.policy to 0.5.0

This release includes a patch that is needed for Neutron to be able to
consume the library.

Related-Bug: #1426082
Related-Bug: #1458945
Change-Id: Ie5e1e49d951637b6599e47078b0c37ebd03722b5

commit_message:
Add devref that explains fullstack testing and its direction

The goal of this doc is to communicate what are full stack tests,
how they benefit you and when would you write such a test.

Additionally I'd like to communicate the way forward, and gather
feedback about any areas in the code that can benefit from full
stack tests, and any additional thoughts!

Change-Id: Ifd4ff9be0ed0184a49df6566d238c31a328cd23f

commit_message:
Disable backup progress notifications for unit tests

We have code somewhere which is firing backup createprogress
notifications into the notifier, which causes random unit
test failures.

Until we determine exactly why this happening, attempt to
avoid this problem in the gate by disabling these notifications.

Related-Bug: #1412513

Change-Id: I50b7946562e757ee26cb68b17b4a5ffcd5f3fabd

It's not an optimization, it makes multiple subnets on an external network work. Without the patch, it doesn't. Since it's allowed by the API I would expect it to work, making this a bug fix."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-02-04 15:09:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Assaf, as far as I understand, they still work, it's just that packets are routed thru upstream link between those subnets. Which is not very efficient but should work, especially for those setups that already use them."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-03-05 23:15:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Whether it "works" or not might depend on the configuration of the upstream router.  In my experience, it has worked but it is inefficient and the router sends ICMP redirects back.  I have a vague memory of working with a router configuration that would not route back on the same interface.'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-03-06 15:53:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Carl, the main question to consider the backport is: Whether it will benefit existing *Icehouse* users? I think upstream router setup is pretty fundamental in cloud design, and so is probably already handled by deployers in some way or another.

It seems to me the backport intends to support setups that were not supported in Icehouse before, and so it's not a strict bug fix but more of a feature enhancement.

What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2015-03-11 10:33:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

stable/icehouse freeze for 2014.1.4

The stable branch is frozen to allow testing before the release. Freeze
exceptions can be proposed on openstack-dev mailing list with [stable] tag in
subject. Once exception request is sent, stable-maint-core team will try to
reach consensus.

More details at: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/StableBranch'}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2015-03-13 23:40:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

stable/icehouse branches open'}, {'account_id': 6502, 'date': '2015-03-23 13:50:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-06-03 16:02:29.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Featureful, Icehouse is about to die, so there is no chance it's going to be merged."}]

commit_message:
Set onlink routes for all subnets on an external network

The addition of the on-link routes gives us some freedom to allocate a
router's IP address from any one of multiple subnets on one external
network.  Different routers can get their IPs from different subnets and
they still have direct on-link connectivity to each other.  For example,
one router with its primary IP from 10.0.0.0/24 and another from
192.168.0.0/24 can communicate directly.  It is important that each
router has on-link routes to *all* of the subnets.

Any router can host floating ips from any of the subnets regardless of
which subnet the primary IP address comes from.

This is an alternative to the "Multiple floating IP pools" section in
the administration guide.  It is a simpler alternative that avoids
having to create multiple external networks.  It is also more flexible
because routers will no longer be restricted to getting floating IPs
from the pool to which they happen to be connected.

DocImpact
Document the procedure for adding subnets to the external network.
Potentially remove the existing procedure for "Multiple floating IP
pools" from the docs.

Conflicts:
	neutron/agent/l3_agent.py
	neutron/agent/linux/interface.py
	neutron/tests/unit/test_l3_agent.py

Change-Id: I2c283f5be0cbb6b5d350cafc1b636c300b796a7b
Closes-Bug: #1312467
(cherry picked from commit fc7cffedbe60ae9da7963373e9072c55700fce5f)

Network: add in additional networks types

The changes in the image model should support all existing driver
types. This adds the supported types in the VMware driver.

the minimum version of oslo.log to be able to switch
