To my knowledge, none of the other clients observe a stable branch model either, so AFAIK if you want bug fixes you have to upgrade to a new version, which is also the reason we're very careful to maintain backwards compatibility in the clients."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-05-13 19:45:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 12321, 'date': '2015-05-13 19:53:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-13 20:31:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

ALL clients have stable/kilo branches now :)
Make sure to talk to Doug next week at Summit, I have no idea how to proceed.
Distros are packaging releases from stable/kilo branches, and we have the same issue (missing Kilo features on stable/kilo client branch) in cinderclient too:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1454818'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-05-14 08:58:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> ALL clients have stable/kilo branches now 

Gah - IMO that's something we weren't sufficiently consulted on and don't really want :(

I've added Steve Baker as he normally handles the heatclient releases, perhaps he'll have thoughts on how to handle this.

If we're forced into a "bugfix only" model for the client stable branches like for the services themselves, we'll just end up carrying a ton of patches downstream IMO.

I guess we'll just end up with a much more relaxed backport policy for clients (e.g backport anything which will actually work with the stable branch version of the service) - either way it's more work for stable maintainers :('}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2015-05-14 09:12:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-05-14 12:51:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Those fixes should be back-ported to stable series release.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-05-14 12:57:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Steve - The spec sat up for review for a while and we discussed it several times at the release meetings during kilo. http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/library-stable-branches.html

We will be discussing it again at the summit on Friday in the release management working session. If you can't make it, send someone from your team."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-05-14 15:35:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Doug: Thanks for the feedback, evidently I missed the prior discussion.

I support capping stable requirements, but not permanently - I think special-casing the clients like this (vs the entire rest of the python community) is a mistake, FWIW.

If a client breaks stable/kilo, it's a bug, we don't need a stable branch to fix that, we just need a means to ensure we don't break the world before we realize (which stable branch caps combined with CI already does)."}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2015-05-14 20:32:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Problem is that on master branch you're automatically getting requirements updates from master global-requirements which will sooner or later get you dependency incompatible with stable/kilo global-requirements.

Alternative is to stay on old deps like Swift and block global reqs updates: https://review.openstack.org/88736"}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2015-05-14 20:48:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I'm totally in favour of a library cap as a way to prevent library releases repeatedly breaking stable CI jobs, but surely the intent was to allow the cap to be raised in a controlled fashion (such as with this change) rather than being forever stuck on a stable branch.

According to semver, 0.6.0 is fully backwards compatible with 0.4.0. Additionally, 0.6.0 has minor feature changes which exposes functionality in stable/kilo heat."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-05-15 11:43:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Problem is that on master branch you're automatically getting requirements updates from master global-requirements which will sooner or later get you dependency incompatible with stable/kilo global-requirements.

But, that's a packaging/distribution problem, surely?  I mean, is it justified to fork the *entire codebase* so we can maintain one file separately between branches (e.g requirements.txt)?

It that's the main motivation behind this change, I can imagine we'll end up backporting nearly every patch to the stable/kilo heatclient branch, probably only ommitting stuff related to new-for-liberty features.

Would an alternative be to say clients must have requirements.txt files which are compatible with all non EOL stable branches (e.g the lower bound for all requirements is taken from the oldest supported stable branch)?  

This would mean we have to ensure clients maintain compatibility with a wider range of library versions, but that's basically what we have to do already, so it's no extra work for developers (whereas the stable branch idea really is a significant additional overhead)."}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2015-05-26 13:04:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> that's a packaging/distribution problem

It is but not only, if you want your master releases to be packaged in e.g. RDO Kilo, upstream requirements.txt need to stay Kilo-compatible, as you mentioned.

BTW what was the conclusion from relmgt session, in etherpad https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/YVR-relmgt-library-releases I see only agenda but no meeting minutes?"}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2015-05-27 02:35:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

The relmgt-library-releases touched on this issue, but was mainly about the release process for libraries and clients.

I talked to Doug about this issue, and he mentioned a not-yet implemented gate job which tests latest clients against stable openstack.

Once this job exists I would be more comfortable about existing stable jobs being pinned on stable clients.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-05-27 08:52:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Ok, so to clarify, distributors (including pip releases) are expected to ignore the stable branches for clients, and we will continue releasing from the master branch, so this should be abandoned and we just document 0.6 is needed for hook support?'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-06-03 16:00:05.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

I'm assuming this should be abandoned, but I'm still not 100% clear on our strategy, I assume we'll just keep releasing from the master branch."}]

commit_message:
Increase stable/kilo python-heatclient upper cap to 0.6

The recently release heatclient 0.6 includes important fixes related
to heat hooks (major new feature for kilo).  Without these fixes, those
consuming stable/kilo heat won't be able to effectively use this new
feature, so bump the upper bound such that folks may distribute the
new version.

Change-Id: I18484acdb8e161e83e690e9fbf45cd02e40c8164

This is great to have this documentation!  I just have a few minor edits'}, {'account_id': 7789, 'date': '2015-05-28 17:04:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

(47 comments)

So at the summit last week alee, redrobot, woodster and arunkant discussed changing the 'creator-only' ACL flag to a 'project-access' flag to avoid confusion on ACLs that have both creator-only set to true AND a list of users that can access the secret/container.

We decided to keep this CR detailing the 'creator-only' flag, but then later put up a new CR to change this to 'project-access'. So please review this CR with the 'creator-only' flag in mind.

So overall, the options we EVENTUALLY want are:
1) Default 4-role RBAC (no ACL, or equivalently 'project-access=true' with no user list)
2) Only 'project-access=false', which makes the secret/container private
3) 'project=access=true' with users on the list...so users in project with correct roles for 4-role RBAC OR ELSE users on the whitelist, can access"}, {'account_id': 7789, 'date': '2015-05-28 17:15:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1091, 'date': '2015-05-28 23:27:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(20 comments)'}, {'account_id': 9914, 'date': '2015-05-29 14:46:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 7789, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:36:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

I also wanted to highlight a REST issue to decide on: should a secret/container be considered to have ACL setting always (even if they are defaulted to project-based only) or not? The former approach makes testing/coding/docs easier because you don't have to worry about things like if a PUT should return 200 or 201, or if some actions like acl GET should return 404 or not. My thinking is that the the no-ACL approach doesn't buy us anything but extra logic to deal with. Other thoughts are welcome here though!"}, {'account_id': 7789, 'date': '2015-06-02 03:40:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Adding documentation for ACLs operations.

Added Secret and Container ACL API reference.
Also added ACL related quick start page.

ACL docs have been updated to account for ACL API changes e.g.
removed per ACL operations.

These doc changes are dependent on code changes in review
https://review.openstack.org//#/c/180888/

Change-Id: Ia8173e7407cc77d4d4a561905ffe8f9f603eb9cb

commit_message:
context.elevated() should use copy.deepcopy()

Currently context.elevated is just doing a copy.copy(self).
This needs to be changed to use copy.deepcopy so that the
list reference is not shared between objects which leaves
the possibility of an admin role leak.

This fix changes context.elevated use copy.deepcopy.

Change-Id: I349c53ccbe9e02ad2a3e84ae897424db9785a170
Closes-bug: 1386932
(cherry picked from commit 285cfaf0954d4c3e320b205c288240c1828476fe)

commit_message:
Clean up temporary images during dockerctl backup

Images created for backup should be cleaned up to
conserve disk space on Fuel Master and reduce
the size of future backups.

Change-Id: I4adf06219bc1edfd97e7cb8ce350d1da47fd9ba3
Closes-Bug: #1437245
(cherry picked from commit c58cf534df27d7f19515fc9b6d48d3a1edc7a041)

commit_message:
Fix backup filename for dockerctl backup

The backup file should contain the timestamp
of the time when the backup was run so that it
can be parsed. This only affected custom backups
because the default backups has the timestamp
in the path.

Change-Id: I184708a5b4077adda9810232a5ae205017a8238e
Closes-Bug: #1461542

commit_message:
Lock Bifrost to Ansible stable-1.9

Due to a change landing in Ansible devel branch, we need to lock
the version to stable-1.9.

Update modules to explicitly define auth_type for compatability with
Ansible 1.9.

This change superceeds: I6dc3842bda19234921cd10fc5836ef8cfdcabb82

Ansible bug: https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/11119

Change-Id: Id4002fd95c09cb765ef9268c8ee35f1d9ce90107
Partial-Bug: #1461025

commit_message:
Transform share and share servers statuses to lowercase

We have several entities in Manila that do have statuses:

- Shares
- Snapshots
- Share Servers
- Share Access Rules

But some share and all share server statuses use uppercase for it.
Make all of them consistent and transform them to lowercase.
Add migrations for it.
Also, remove two unused statuses and reuse all statuses from common place.

Change-Id: I53e6a768c98977d3d94e761349b7446a9dfb4936
Closes-Bug: #1459598

commit_message:
User should be able to update allocation pool values.

Steps to reproduce it:
1. Select an existing subnet.
2. In the subnet detail, change the allocation pools value.
3. Click Save.
4. Click the changed subnet detail and check the allocation pool value.

Root cause: The problem is that we only allow a new subnet to set the allocation pool.
Seems like we can do that via api during update and so we should enable that on Horizon.

Change-Id: I9e6b0ee427ca9af82c4ed80abc1e7c19fe81641f
Closes-bug: 1458803
Closes-bug: 1458769

commit_message:
Move rally.benchmark.runners.base module

Directory rally/benchmark/runners contains only one module base.py.
There are no reasons to keep this directory, so this patch makes the
following rename:
    rally.benchmark.runners.base -> rally.benchmark.runner

Also, this patch contain several minor doc fixes.

Change-Id: I2a810a95d82b99fa01f3e90eee17466a98b5d200

commit_message:
Update Chapter 3. Designing for Cloud Controllers

Update Identity backends [Chapter 3. Designing
for Cloud Controllers and Cloud Management]
in OpenStack Operations Guide removing PAM
and adding memcached in list of possible back ends.

Change-Id: Iec1c5a0c81a0658c513144be64bf87d21d0231f7
Closes-Bug: #1454106

commit_message:
Change "Devstack" to "DevStack" in headings

This patch changes "Devstack" to "DevStack" and
"Openstack" to "OpenStack" in HEAT developer
documentation, so that their uses can be unified.

Closes-Bug: #1461456

Change-Id: Ie01b1a87205430672e56a41a51764b975090c1f9

commit_message:
Python3: use six.iteritems() instead of dict.iteritems()

This also adds a check to neutron/hacking/checks.py that should catch this
error in the future.

Blueprint: neutron-python3

commit_message:
os-net-config templates to configure vlans

This patch adds 5 new role templates to help configure
a vlans on top for each of the overcloud roles. This
patch adds vlans on top of a single NIC attached to
the control plane network (already used for provisioning).

The patch also includes an environment file to
enable configuration of vlans by simply sourcing this file.

Change-Id: Ibc40e452dec9b372ff10442aab2bddaf382b0a2f

commit_message:
Move application to current projects up in tag page

Feedback from operators in a user committee session pointed out which
projects a tag is applied to is one of the most useful things on each
tag's page.  So move the 'application to current projects' section up in
the page so it is easier to find.

Change-Id: Ib7b0aa250f950398e0abd20d35a1ea252b057d4c

commit_message:

I like this one, i think it should solve all of the use-cases I had. Just unit test changes and it should be ready to go?'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-05-27 17:12:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Patrick, Winston, and John,

Uploaded a new patch set based on the team decision. Please note that free virtual capacity is already used for decision making for thin luns. That is why there is no additional change on that.

The problem we are trying to fix here is we also used free physical capacity for thin luns. I modified it in the latest patch set so that it now only checks if free physical capacity is 0 for thin. If it is already 0, we don't allow any more thin lun to be provisioned. Another idea is not to check free physical capacity for thin lun at all. I'm fine with that as well.

Let me know what you think. Thanks."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-05-27 17:53:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Patrick's comments were hidden behind all those CI reports. I just saw it. Good to know it works for you now.

Winston and John, any comments on this patch set? Unit tests will be added soon."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-05-27 18:01:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

[{'created': '2015-05-26 22:35:06.000000000', 'message': 'Add flag assume_virtual_capacity_consumed

For thin provisioning, we introduce a flag assume_virtual_capacity_consumed.
If it is True, the filter scheduler will deduct the size of the new volume
and assume the new volume to be created will be fully consumed. If this
flag is False, the filter scheduler will not deduct the size of the new
volume and assume nothing will be consumed until the user really starts
to write data on the volume. This is a compromised approach so that this
can be handled differently based on how the admin wants to use the thinly
provisioned space.

Change-Id: I4c8904445654db839c25ded420915f83c3756f94
Closes-Bug: #1458976

commit_message:
Fix capacity filter to allow oversubscription

Currently the capacity filter does not allow oversubscrition
if the free physical capacity is less than the new volume size.
This was based on the assumption that a new thinly provisioned
volume will be consumed right away. This assumption does not
allow us to take full advantage of thin provisioning.

The fix is to allow oversubscription if thin provisioning is
supported and max_over_subscription_ratio is greater than or
equal to 1. The free physical capacity will not be used to
compare with the new volume size for a backend that supports
oversubscription in thin provisioning. The oversubscription
ratio and virtual free capacity will still be used to decide
whether a backend can be chosen for thin provisioning.

Closes-Bug: #1458976
Change-Id: I4c8904445654db839c25ded420915f83c3756f94

commit_message:
[Heat] Pass parameters, files and env  for heat stacks

Some heat templates can contain parameters, files and
environment dependencies that cannot be used with the current
scenario realization in rally. So the patch provides
"parameters", "files" and "environment" input parameters
in rally scenarios that allow to use these inputs
for stack create/update operations.

Change-Id: I6639d002a140659f677a6ed6f08b7741713a4e5f

commit_message:
Remove oslo.serialization from requirements.txt

Change I00f66b0f3c8e9f688429ee78bd51608a4dcac140 added
oslo.serialization to requirements.txt on stable to unwedge the gate due
to keystone on stable testing against master level keystoneclient which
required oslo.serialization.

Later, change I079fa77501b8987a4724d03a792b084a6d853e21 fixed the
testing problem by running the tests in a venv, so we can just
remove oslo.serialization from keystone's requirements.txt now.

Closes-Bug: #1434152

Change-Id: I224a3652fba170da34da9935e6f8b4a161a856d2

commit_message:
Remove jenkins, launchpad and gerrit docs

All of that information can be found at
http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html, so just make the
link to developers.html more prominent in development.environment

* Rename development.environment to a shorter title, Developer quickstart.

Change-Id: I1460e6c86a7e0a1efb4a81c6c5cb594476171214

commit_message:
Add support for HGST Solutions to devstack localrc

Adds a simple cinder_backends/hgst script which sets appropriate
ini values defined in a localrc using HGST_* parameters.

Depends on the HGST Volume driver described at:
(bp/add-volume-driver-hgst-solutions) for functionality, but can
be tested without that patch.

Trivial bashate fixes.  "tox -v -ebashate" is now my friend.

Change-Id: I55395ef26dcbeaadc100d7603c99924a0e9dd68d
Closes-Bug: bug/1460130

commit_message:
Split list filtering into _utils

The inventory module wants to use these. Also, they are not actually
methods - they are simple functions. Split them out for sanity.

Change-Id: Ib46f788da0f92ed49d350facc0a59cb1697f06ec

It could even be argued that the admin endpoint should not appear in the service catalog if it is not available to a user, as that is the kind of reason the SC comes _after_ authentication.  I'd be happy for that to be our test as it is simple and global.  However, I don't think that is the case in practice and we'll need another general solution.  Would you please to file a bug on this if one does not already exist?"}, {'account_id': 13252, 'date': '2015-06-02 14:13:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Change-Id: I68214d2680bad907f9d04ad3ca2f62cf3feee028
Closes-Bug: #1459629
'}, {'created': '2015-06-02 15:00:52.000000000', 'message': 'Fix security group list command

Security group list command tries to get a project list and
this may fail with a multitude of exceptions including but
not limited to 401, 404, ConnectionRefused and EndpointNotFound.
Rather than try to capture every possibility, this patch just
catches the base class.  Converting project ids to names is

Closes-Bug: #1459629
'}]
commit_message:
Fix security group list command

Security group list command tries to get a project list and
this may fail with a multitude of exceptions including but
not limited to 401, 404, ConnectionRefused and EndpointNotFound.
Rather than try to capture every possibility, this patch just
catches the base class.  Converting project ids to names is
less important than having a working security group list command.

Change-Id: I68214d2680bad907f9d04ad3ca2f62cf3feee028
Closes-Bug: #1459629

commit_message:
Erase mnesia if a rabbit node cannot join the cluster

W/o this fix, the situation is possible when a
rabbit node would stuck in a start/stop loop failing
to join the cluster with an error:
"no_running_cluster_nodes, You cannot leave a cluster
if no online nodes are present."

This is an issue because the rabbit node should always
be able to join the cluster, if it was ordered to start
by pacemaker RA.

The solution is to force the mnesia reset, if the
rabbit node cannot join the cluster on post-start
notify. Note, that for the master starting, the node
wouldn't be reset. So, the mnesia will be kept intact
at least on the resource master.

Partial-bug: #1461509

Change-Id: I69bc13266a1dc784681b2677ae5616bfc28cf54f
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

[{'created': '2015-05-29 18:58:10.000000000', 'message': "Reschedules sometimes do not allocate networks

Changes to instance.system_metadata weren't properly being saved
to the DB. The change to 'network_allocated' would be written to
the DB but not updated on the instance object. When the network
was cleaned up before a reschedule, the object would not notice
network_allocated' getting set to False, and not write the change
to the DB. After the reschedule, the instance would still have
'network_allocated' set to True, and skip allocating a network.
The node would go active with no network.

Since this is happening in the _allocate_network_async greenthread,
the solution is not to save in the async thread. The main thread
and the async thread share a reference to the same object and the
main thread waits for the async thread to finish before the final
save, so saving is unnecessary. I added comments on the
instance.save() calls that were part of the race so they don't get
removed or changed and reintroduce this bug.

Also, update the relevant test from mox to mock.

Change-Id: I937ec020b46703392bd603008d03af0f422bc0d1
(cherry picked from commit 717aa88f14e549d9e5d8b252ba7128e3dac991b6)

commit_message:
Reschedules sometimes do not allocate networks

Changes to instance.system_metadata weren't properly being saved
to the DB. The change to 'network_allocated' would be written to
the DB but not updated on the instance object. When the network
was cleaned up before a reschedule, the object would not notice
network_allocated' getting set to False, and not write the change
to the DB. After the reschedule, the instance would still have
'network_allocated' set to True, and skip allocating a network.
The node would go active with no network.

Since this is happening in the _allocate_network_async greenthread,
the solution is not to save in the async thread. The main thread
and the async thread share a reference to the same object and the
main thread waits for the async thread to finish before the final
save, so saving is unnecessary. I added comments on the
instance.save() calls that were part of the race so they don't get
removed or changed and reintroduce this bug.

Also, update the relevant test from mox to mock.

Closes-Bug: #1460176

Change-Id: I937ec020b46703392bd603008d03af0f422bc0d1
(cherry picked from commit 717aa88f14e549d9e5d8b252ba7128e3dac991b6)

commit_message:
Fix the controller with three nodes for HA.

The graphics in this section show two Controller nodes for HA, but each
production environment should contain an odd number of Controllers so
these graphics should show three Controller nodes. It may be appropriate to
mention the quorum issue and link to the HA Guide for information about how to
turn quorum off for non-production environments.
-----------------------------------
Built: 2015-03-13T09:16:07 00:00

xml:id: example_architecture

commit_message:
Avoid using SenlinException class directly

We should never use the base SenlinException class directly because
there is no corresponding error code corresponding to the base class.

Change-Id: I1877db6afa746db1de6b383daff4f02fdecb4603

commit_message:
Centralize Barbican API Config

This centralizes all config options into config.py,
eliminating a race condition where not all config options
from modules may have been registered by the time the
config file is parsed. Plugins are now provided a
separate config object, to which they can add their
own individual options before parsing the config file themselves.

Change-Id: I737bfe092ff71a1275f27de5b9328e9d23032a24
Closes-Bug: #1459448

commit_message:
Raise exception when backup volume-backed instance

This patch will be backported to Juno and Icehouse so that
Nova can fail immediately to let user know that it's not
supported in that release.

Partial-Bug: #1313573

NOTE: This conflict is because there is a new parameter
named 'id' for method:
common.raise_http_conflict_for_instance_invalid_state.

Conflicts:
        nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/admin_actions.py
        nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/create_backup.py

Change-Id: Ic84fa9e0b9c2d7b6cf49955aa4f0d44ade2b5397
(cherry picked from commit 2b94135865af710dc9c7210d23e1df5f54afed62)

[{'created': '2015-06-03 13:06:24.000000000', 'message': 'Handle indexer connections more cleanly in tests

In some situations (especially low concurrency) it was possible to
run out of available postgres connections during test runs. This was
happening because the gabbi tests call gnocchi.rest.app:setup_app
with every test and were doing it without passing an indexer
reference. This caused setup_app to create a new one.

Now, instead, the gabbi tests flex some globals to insure that an
indexer, per test suite, is passed to setup_app.

setup_app is changed to _only_ call index.connect() when a new
indexer is created, making the assumption that if callers have
provided an indexer, they have also connected. This assumption is
born out by the tests.

The alembic online migration called disconnect() for cleanliness
(because it creates and connects its own indexer).

With these changes the tests will pass with only 6 available
postgresql connection running with a concurrency of 2, so the -N 200
has been removed.

Change-Id: I00430a45ab471b70bc747b9811ec984ab1493eaa
'}]
commit_message:
Handle indexer connections more cleanly in tests

In some situations (especially low concurrency) it was possible to
run out of available postgres connections during test runs. This was
happening because the gabbi tests call gnocchi.rest.app:setup_app
with every test and were doing it without passing an indexer
reference. This caused setup_app to create a new one.

Now, instead, the gabbi tests flex some globals to insure that an
indexer, per test suite, is passed to setup_app.

setup_app is changed to _only_ call index.connect() when a new
indexer is created, making the assumption that if callers have
provided an indexer, they have also connected. This assumption is
born out by the tests.

The alembic online migration called disconnect() for cleanliness
(because it creates and connects its own indexer).

With these changes the tests will pass with only 6 available
postgresql connection running with a concurrency of 2, so the -N 200
has been removed.

Change-Id: I00430a45ab471b70bc747b9811ec984ab1493eaa

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-05 13:02:11.000000000', 'message': 'Reuse the undercloud service passwords as db passwords.

We need to stop using "unset" as the password for all databases. Ideally we
would add a "XxxxDSN" parameter (e.g. KeystoneDSN) but to remain consistent
with the overcloud for now we reuse the service passwords

Change-Id: I35c4fa3478eea92f81aa381fd2ab5fac5aae849f
'}]
commit_message:
Reuse the undercloud service passwords as db passwords.

We need to stop using "unset" as the password for all databases. Ideally we
would add a "XxxxDSN" parameter (e.g. KeystoneDSN) but to remain consistent
with the overcloud for now we reuse the service passwords

Change-Id: I35c4fa3478eea92f81aa381fd2ab5fac5aae849f

Ensure the hieradata directory isn't world readable

This directory contains all kinds of secrets and shouldn't be
readable to non privileged users.

Change-Id: Ia941e0f0a3ae5cf50259fbb8e13375ab2989eaa1

commit_message:
Depend on keystoneclient for expiration checking

The AccessInfo object that we build moments after doing expiration
checking implements its expiry checks in exactly the same way.

Build AccessInfo object earlier and use this for expiration checking.
This will in future allow us to do additional checks like bind checking
using the AccessInfo rather than raw token data.

Change-Id: I71d6f4a16fda612c7ffe09f3f1e90fac484f2834

commit_message:
Remove bogus conditional from node_update

We have a conditional in the node_update() method checking if a user
is trying to modify the power_state of a node via PATCH, that won't
never get triggered because power_state is an internal attribute and
the request will fail on the API side.

Plus it makes no sense for checking power_state but not other states
such as provision_state, console_enabled, etc...

The NodeInWrongPowerState exception was also removed because it's not
being used anywhere else.

Change-Id: Ibc726fb9b91af8ca0e3880350d2a499b9501a7f3

commit_message:
TraitText value restricted to max length 255

Trait_text has a sqlalchemy model definition with
value column as Text type, but the migrate scripts
defined the column type as String(255) leading to
Sqlalchemy exception when indexing trait with large
text.

This fixes the TraitText model value as String(255)
to match the migrate script definition and crops
the text input to 255 characters.

Change-Id: I55eee4e9fcdee8d05f3598a9bc0368bc92a9b238
Closes-Bug: 1447647

commit_message:
Move eventlet using commands into own directory

The api server does not need and should not use eventlet since it is
now using a multi-process capable web server from Werkzeug so is
kept above the eventlet directory where eventlet overriding
happens.

Partially-Implements: blueprint remove-web-eventlet
Change-Id: I377a105a5e53c3c548354877cac477609bf06b63

It is possible to import `zmq` module from `eventlet.green` only if an
actual Python interpreter has pyzmq package installed. But `zmq` object is used
within driver unconditionally. Using of `try_import` and obtained
NoneType object instead of `zmq` object causes raising of unobvious exceptions
all around the driver.

Current solution: Fixed `zmq` import from eventlet.green. 'pyzmq' added to
requirements. We need it to test the module. If dispensable imported object
used unconditionally we can stumble an `AttributeError` with `NoneType`.

Alternative: we can continue to use `try_import` with some restrictions.
Before any code from the driver module be used we need to check is `zmq`
not `None` and if it is - raise `ImportError`. If we will not add `pyzmq` to
the requirements we couldn't test the driver with CI gates.

commit_message:
Required pyzmq for 0mq driver

It is possible to import `zmq` module from `eventlet.green` only if an
actual Python interpreter has pyzmq package installed. But `zmq` object is used
within driver unconditionally. Using of `try_import` and obtained
NoneType object instead of `zmq` object causes raising of unobvious exceptions
all around the driver.

Current solution: Fixed `zmq` import from eventlet.green. 'pyzmq' added to
requirements. We need it to test the module. If dispensable imported object
used unconditionally we can stumble an `AttributeError` with `NoneType`.

Alternative: we can continue to use `try_import` with some restrictions.
Before any code from the driver module be used we need to check is `zmq`
not `None` and if it is - raise `ImportError`. If we will not add `pyzmq` to
the requirements we couldn't test the driver with CI gates.

Change-Id: Ib3957a736b0dca2279f439f2099374d2adbf1659
Closes-Bug: #1373350

commit_message:
Use fasteners library for interprocess locks

This library provides the interprocess lock code
shared by oslo.concurrency, taskflow, and tooz, so
we can just use it instead of having something similar.

Change-Id: Ie6dc318b2c1fc86605bb48f6909df7f1aa6a216f

[{'created': '2015-04-17 09:28:07.000000000', 'message': "Allow disabling the evacuate cleanup mechanism in compute manager

This mechanism attempts to destroy any locally-running instances on
startup if instance.host != self.host. The assumption is that the
instance has been evacuated and is safely running elsewhere. This is
a dangerous assumption to make, so this patch adds a configuration
variable to disable this behavior if it's not desired.

Note that disabling it may have implications for the case where
instances *were* evacuated, given potential shared resources.
To counter that problem, this patch also makes _init_instance()
skip initialization of the instance if it appears to be owned
by another host, logging a prominent warning in that case.

As a result, if you have destroy_after_evacuate=False and you start
a nova compute with an incorrect hostname, or run it twice from
another host, then the worst that will happen is you get log
warnings about the instances on the host being ignored. This should
be an indication that something is wrong, but still allow for
fixing it without any loss. If the configuration option is disabled
and a legitimate evacuation does occur, simply enabling it and then
restarting the compute service will cause the cleanup to occur.

This is added to the workarounds config group because it is really
only relevant while evacuate is fundamentally broken in this way.
It needs to be refactored to be more robust, and once that is done,
this should be able to go away.

(cherry picked from commit 922148ac45c5a70da8969815b4f47e3c758d6974)

Conflicts:
	nova/compute/manager.py
	nova/tests/compute/test_compute_mgr.py
	nova/utils.py
In nova/utils.py a new section has been introduced but
only the option addessed by this backport has been included

DocImpact: New configuration option, and peril warning
Partial-Bug: #1419785
Change-Id: Ib9a3c72c096822dd5c65c905117ae14994c73e99
"}, {'created': '2015-04-20 09:51:21.000000000', 'message': "Allow disabling the evacuate cleanup mechanism in compute manager

This mechanism attempts to destroy any locally-running instances on
startup if instance.host != self.host. The assumption is that the
instance has been evacuated and is safely running elsewhere. This is
a dangerous assumption to make, so this patch adds a configuration
variable to disable this behavior if it's not desired.

Note that disabling it may have implications for the case where
instances *were* evacuated, given potential shared resources.
To counter that problem, this patch also makes _init_instance()
skip initialization of the instance if it appears to be owned
by another host, logging a prominent warning in that case.

As a result, if you have destroy_after_evacuate=False and you start
a nova compute with an incorrect hostname, or run it twice from
another host, then the worst that will happen is you get log
warnings about the instances on the host being ignored. This should
be an indication that something is wrong, but still allow for
fixing it without any loss. If the configuration option is disabled
and a legitimate evacuation does occur, simply enabling it and then
restarting the compute service will cause the cleanup to occur.

commit_message:
Allow disabling the evacuate cleanup mechanism in compute manager

This mechanism attempts to destroy any locally-running instances on
startup if instance.host != self.host. The assumption is that the
instance has been evacuated and is safely running elsewhere. This is
a dangerous assumption to make, so this patch adds a configuration
variable to disable this behavior if it's not desired.

Note that disabling it may have implications for the case where
instances *were* evacuated, given potential shared resources.
To counter that problem, this patch also makes _init_instance()
skip initialization of the instance if it appears to be owned
by another host, logging a prominent warning in that case.

As a result, if you have destroy_after_evacuate=False and you start
a nova compute with an incorrect hostname, or run it twice from
another host, then the worst that will happen is you get log
warnings about the instances on the host being ignored. This should
be an indication that something is wrong, but still allow for
fixing it without any loss. If the configuration option is disabled
and a legitimate evacuation does occur, simply enabling it and then
restarting the compute service will cause the cleanup to occur.

This is added to the workarounds config group because it is really
only relevant while evacuate is fundamentally broken in this way.
It needs to be refactored to be more robust, and once that is done,
this should be able to go away.

Conflicts:
        nova/compute/manager.py
        nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute.py
        nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute_mgr.py
        nova/utils.py

NOTE: In nova/utils.py a new section has been introduced but
only the option addessed by this backport has been included.

DocImpact: New configuration option, and peril warning
Partial-Bug: #1419785
(cherry picked from commit 922148ac45c5a70da8969815b4f47e3c758d6974)

-- squashed with commit --

Create a 'workarounds' config group.

This group is for very specific reasons.

If you're:
- Working around an issue in a system tool (e.g. libvirt or qemu) where the fix
  is in flight/discussed in that community.
- The tool can be/is fixed in some distributions and rather than patch the code
  those distributions can trivially set a config option to get the "correct"
  behavior.
This is a good place for your workaround.

(cherry picked from commit b1689b58409ab97ef64b8cec2ba3773aacca7ac5)

--

Change-Id: Ib9a3c72c096822dd5c65c905117ae14994c73e99

commit_message:
Apply urlize filter to Last operation of environment component table

Before any link displayed by reporter in 'Last operation' field of
murano environment component would be displayed as plain text. This
change applies urlize filter to the value of the field, making it easier
for users to navigate to services, provided by the environment

Closes-Bug: #1461481
Change-Id: I8543bc58ea6663770253953e5e3c182800dc1323

commit_message:
Added config file support in freezerc

The freezer client now support arguments
taken from a config file. Command line and config
argments can be set, but command line always has
precedence ofer config file.

Change-Id: I1327fdcd920eefa95fcb6f387d2f3c3a52aab32e
Implements: blueprint config-file

commit_message:
Add networking-bgpvpn repo to Neutron.

The networking-bgpvpn repository, currently in stackforge, is a Neutron service plugin
for interconnecting Neutron networks and BGP-based VPNs.

https://github.com/stackforge/networking-bgpvpn

Following discussions during the summit, the identified next-step is to move this proposal
under the Neutron "big tent" (related docs about adding repositories like this to Neutron
can be found here: https://review.openstack.org/175952 ).

The implementation is an early implementation of specifications initially proposed for
the Neutron main repo for Liberty release.  The specs will move in this new project and
the implementation will be updated to reflect comments made on the spec:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/177740/

This implementation is designed to delegate the actual implementation work to
drivers, targeting for instance such or such "SDN controller". A lightweight
implementation based on bagpipe-bgp [1] is already provided and suitable for running
CI tests.

Change-Id: I6817d63e489409edf382eba2f947f3451d9bd5fe

commit_message:
Add grafyaml to infra

Based off JJB, grafyaml is a tool to build Grafana dashboards from yaml
files. This allows for the same automation we see with Jenkins, but for
Grafana.

Change-Id: I5d6dfe128bc7ce3c6dec798ab0748f057983f2e5
Depends-On: I91bde2c88788d3b3e65f6a28caed4d35ce45a463
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Update the deprecated group/name to Kilo release

For Kilo release, there are many deprecated group/name in conf files of openstack,
so we need to change the deprecated group/name to new group/name.

blueprint conf-section-update-for-kilo
Closes-bug: #1436170

Change-Id: Icf361d2132553bbc20b517c8b08f6df2d069e8bb

commit_message:
Add TC-owned project-team-guide repo

The TC has a subgroup working on documentation for project teams
as OpenStack grows to encompass more projects.  This is a repo to
host that documentation.

Change-Id: Ib4f9934ca6d0946ca3f633f95c9336227bd6de28
Depends-On: I46292749d645f5f8e99c4f52c975c79bb446c6db

commit_message:
-v trumps -d on the CLI

This patch updates the handling of the --debug and --verbose
options so that if both are specified then log level is set to
DEBUG.

Change-Id: I65d5665631f5575d1c8343bb7c1b197a61e0e176
Closes-bug: #1450586

commit_message:
Wire --vlan-trunk-ids into devtest_testenv.sh

Updates devtest_testenv.sh so that it supports
sending the --vlan-trunk-ids arguments to
setup-network.

commit_message:
setup-network: add support for vlan trunks

This patch adds a new --vlan-trunk-ids option to the
setup-network script so that can be used to enable trunked
VLAN IDs.

The goal is to allow VLAN traffic to flow between our VMs
in a virtualized development environment.

Normal untagged traffic is still allowed on VLAN ID 0. This
should allow normal ctlplane provisioning traffic to continue
flowing if VLANs are used on the same bridge.

Change-Id: Ic5fbb2a54049c6e6bd7a64317268cf79b21020ba

commit_message:
Allow use of ssl for public api endpoints

There are two methods included: Setting $service_certificate will
enable SSL for all public endpoints with the same cert file, while
service-specific certificate settings allow using a cert file for
just one service.

Change-Id: I6f87ed2ebbea08ff1a0dff981559c8f4fc8b67cc

commit_message:
Remove the deprecated external authentication methods

class: LegacyDomain, LegacyDefaultDomain, ExternalDomain,
ExternalDefault have been marked as deprecated since ICEHOUSE,
Currently, Liberty release cycle has been opened, so we should
remove them from the code base.

Co-Authored-By: Dolph Mathews <dolph.mathews@gmail.com>
Partially implements: blueprint removed-as-of-liberty
Change-Id: If81ea4a05488cd1cb92fb9ea6171de4b8342da6a

Add scenario to modify Cinder volume metadata

This performs multiple modifications of Cinder volume metadata and
benchmarks metadata modifications and deletions.

commit_message:
Refactor Huawei Volume driver

This blueprint is an attempt to refactor the Huawei volume driver in liberty.
We will add a base dirver to implement the basic functions that the Cinder driver required.
The sub-class will inherit the base driver according to different storages.
the following diragram shows the structure of the newest Huawei volume driver

        +---------------+ +------------------+ +--------------------+
        | ISCSIDriver | | HuaweiBaseDriver | | FibreChannelDriver |
        +---------+-----+ +----+-------------+ +----+-----------+----+
                  | | | |
                  | | |__________ |
                  | | | |
              +---+--------------------+ +---+--------------------+
              | Huawei18000ISCSIDriver | | Huawei18000FCDriver |
              +-------------+----------+ +-------------+----------+

Change-Id: I33f30fb5448abcffc0916329bc5aa976e7dbad41
Implements: blueprint refactor-huawei-volume-driver

commit_message:
Add class to deal with clouds.yaml support

For running functional tests on devstack nodes, it's important to be
able to get the appropriate credentials. Use the clouds.yaml that is
newly written by devstack and os-client-config to pull a few well
defined sets of credentials.

Change-Id: Ibd2d473fce878424e8a6d1c76e81088e575e619b

commit_message:
Refactor Huawei Volume driver

This blueprint is an attempt to refactor the Huawei volume driver in liberty.
We will add a base dirver to implement the basic functions that the Cinder driver required.
The sub-class will inherit the base driver according to different storages.
the following diragram shows the structure of the newest Huawei volume driver

        +---------------+ +------------------+ +--------------------+
        | ISCSIDriver | | HuaweiBaseDriver | | FibreChannelDriver |
        +---------+-----+ +----+-------------+ +----+-----------+----+
                  | | | |
                  | | |__________ |
                  | | | |
              +---+--------------------+ +---+--------------------+
              | Huawei18000ISCSIDriver | | Huawei18000FCDriver |
              +-------------+----------+ +-------------+----------+

Change-Id: Ia90c149da66a9cee664b8de8d4a8af1a7eb7eede
Implements: bp/refactor-huawei-volume-driver

commit_message:
cleanup murano docs in the image_builders folder

standart to standard
clean up capitalizations that are unnecessary
harware to hardware
added transition words the a where needed
avaible changed to available
emtpy should be empty
unatteded should be unattended
Manualy should be manually
Performes should be performs
scrtips should be scripts
changed docs to comply with doc conventions
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/Conventions

Change-Id: I5324053f4eed28a3f7b37b5fe2b334e7d374ad13
